n-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">.<br /> </p> </div> </span><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142519#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/153650/142054?from=rss_related\">3招简单将博客转换成电子书</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/139717?from=rss_related\">iPhone版WordPress支持视频、更好的本地草稿管理</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/ecauses/138877?from=rss_related\">非营利组织开展短信活动的五大挑战</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/155419/136786?from=rss_related\">[信息视图]短信发送的上升趋势</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/106206/137194?from=rss_related\">开车用手机大大增加了交通事故死亡</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422809894/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142519\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422809894/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422809894/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>") (pubDate nil "Tue, 12 Oct 2010 16:32:00 +0800") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142519") (dc:creator nil "pestwave") (fs:srclink nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142519") (fs:srcfeed nil "http://www.yeeyan.org/feed/category/410") (fs:itemid nil "feedsky/yeeyan-tech/~8024233/422809894/5032246"))) ("Google自动驾驶车：千里之行，始于轮下" "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/googles_self-driving_car_where_it_stands_in_histor.php\">Google\\'s Self-Driving Car is Just the Beginning</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/134838\">tintinlock</a></p><blockquote>Google announced this weekend that it has developed a car that can drive itself. A small fleet of the vehicles has logged more than 1,000 miles of entirely automated driving and 140,000 miles of driving with only occasional human intervention.</blockquote> <p>Google在本周宣布<a href=\"http://www.techmeme.com/101010/p21#a101010p21\" target=\"_blank\">它们研发了一款自动驾驶的汽车</a>。一小队这样的汽车已经全自动地行驶了1，000英里，另外在很少的人工干预下还行驶了140，000英里。</p> <blockquote>It's a development of historic significance: few events have changed the experience of life on earth as much as last century's proliferation of hundreds of millions of automobiles. The automobile was a revolution in personal autonomy, but it came with great costs. Now we've entered an era when that personal autonomy will become automated and some of the automobile's costs could be mitigated as a result. As a technologist, I find it helpful to understand the emergence of the fabled self-driving car as a convergence of three trends: the Internet of Things, Big Data and Real-Time Technology. Those trends are poised to go far beyond a self-driving car.</blockquote> <p>这是里程碑式的发展：上个世纪，汽车如雨后春笋般出现，深刻地改变了人类在地球上的生活，此后在没有什么事件能与之相提并论。个人自主权因为汽车的出现发生了变革，但同时代价是巨大的。不过，如今我们即将进入私人汽车的新时代——驾驶的完全自动化，以及因此减少的代价。作为一个技术专家，我觉得，为了更好地认识这种神话般的自动驾驶车的意义，我们可以将它视作三种趋势的集合：物联网，大数据集，以及实时科技。当然，这三者的发展绝不局限于自动驾驶车。</p> <blockquote>The Internet of Things</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">物联网：</span></p> <blockquote>The personal automobile was invented near the end of the 19th century and popularized throughout the 20th - approximately 600 million now traverse a world of roads. There is 1 car for every 11 people on earth, but sometimes it's hard to remember that - they can seem so ubiquitous. </blockquote> <p>私人汽车发明于19世纪末，流行于20世纪——大约有6亿辆车行驶在这个世界的路上。平均每11人才拥有一辆车——难以置信，它们明明无处不在。</p> <blockquote>As widespread and significant as they are, though, automobiles themselves have been to date relatively unconnected to each other. They are big, dumb, fast-moving hunks of metal. Essential, in fact, to keep apart from one another as they hurtle down the highway.</blockquote> <p>尽管汽车如此广泛和重要，它们仍然过时了——因为每一辆车都与其他的车不相往来，它们只是一块块默默赶路的金属。</p> <blockquote>\"Your car should drive itself,\" Google CEO Eric Schmidt foreshadowed in a public statement last week, days before the Google self-driving car was unveiled. \"It's amazing to me that we let humans drive cars. It's a bug that cars were invented before computers.\"</blockquote> <p>“你的车应该自己掌握方向盘，”Google的CEO Eric Schmidt在上周的一个<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/the_future_of_search_is_mobile_autonomous_serendipitous_says_google_ceo_eric_schmidt.php\" target=\"_blank\">公开声明</a>上如此预言——几天后Google发布了他们的自动驾驶车。“我不敢相信我们居然让人来开车。汽车在电脑之前被发明出来简直是个历史故障。”</p> <blockquote>The instrumentation and networking of previously offline objects, like cars, buildings, roads and more, may represent the next big stage in the evolution of technology. A network-connected car in particular - primarily navigated by artificial intelligence able to leverage a world of data hosted in the cloud - promises big gains in safety, efficiency and quality of life for everyday drivers.</blockquote> <p>科技革新的下一个舞台是把曾经与互联网分离的物品——汽车，建筑，公路等等——仪表化和联网化。以联网的汽车为例：存储在云端的数据恒河沙数，通过人工智能四两拨千斤，汽车便能由AI来导航。这种方式将带来安全性，效率和舒适度的巨大提升。</p> <blockquote>This product illustrates the potential for what's called the Internet of Things in a big way, but it should be understood in the context of the much larger trend. \"Trying to determine the market size of the Internet of Things is like trying to calculate the market for plastics, circa 1940,\" says Georgetown University Communication, Culture & Technology professor Michael Nelson, the former director of Internet Technology at IBM, and the former director of Technology Policy with the Federal Communications Commission, in a February report by The Hammersmith Group. \"At that time, it was difficult to imagine that plastics could be in every-thing. If you look at information processing in the same way, you begin to see the vast range of objects into which logic, processors, or actuators could be embedded.\"</blockquote> <p>这种汽车淋漓尽致地展示了物联网的美好图景，但我们还应将这个图景置于更大的时代背景中去看。“想要给物联网的市场规模下个定论，就像在1940年预测塑料的市场规模一样，”乔治敦大学文化与科技交流教授Michael Nelson在<a href=\"http://thehammersmithgroup.com/research.html\" target=\"_blank\">The Hammersmith Group</a>二月的一份报告中说。他曾是IBM互联网科技部的前任主管，联邦通讯委员会科技政策部门的前任主管。“那个时候（1940年），很难想象塑料会被用在各种物品上。如果你把现在的信息处理看作那时的塑料，那么你就能设想到逻辑处理器能被嵌入进多少东西。”</p> <blockquote>Big Data</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">大数据集：</span></p> <blockquote>How is Google able to drive a car? In part because its software has access to an incredible amount of very detailed data: maps of the world, speed limit information, live video of a car's surroundings, sharp computer vision analysis of what that live video contains and big-picture data about an emerging network of cars in motion on the road.</blockquote> <p>Google是如何让汽车自动驾驶的？部分原因在于，它的软件部分可以获得难以置信的详尽数据：世界地图，限速信息，周边环境的实时影像，清晰的可视化分析，以及由公路上汽车的动态所交织出的巨大网状图像。</p> <blockquote>Multiply that by not just one car, but countless cars throughout our roads and you've got a whole lot of data being processed. </blockquote> <p>这还仅仅是一辆车所能获得的信息，将它乘于汽车的总数——抱歉，这些车已经数不胜数了。想想你能得到多少信息吧。</p> <blockquote>Where there are network-connected devices, there are waves of data made available. Where there is big data, there are opportunities for pattern analysis, rational decisions and recommendations based on that data. </blockquote> <p>只要有联网设备，就有源源不断的数据产生。只要有大量数据，就不愁得不出图样分析，理性决策以及合理建议。</p> <blockquote>It's hard to know whether Google's self-driving cars ought to be called recommendation technology based on big data, or whether this is going beyond recommendation and into directive commands. </blockquote> <p>很难说Google的自动驾驶车应该被称为基于大数据集的推荐技术，还是它已经超越推荐技术，直接发号施令了。</p> <blockquote>Big data is, in large part, about decision making. A Google self-driving car will make it easier to make decisions about the important parts of driving by automating the parts that don't require human decision-making.</blockquote> <p>从很大范围来说，大数据集事关决策。一辆Google的自动驾驶车会让驾驶时进行重大决策变得更简单，因为它自动处理了不需要人类参与的决策部分。</p> <blockquote>As Michael E. Driscoll wrote this spring,</blockquote> <p>正如Michael E. Driscoll<a href=\"http://dataspora.com/blog/new-tools-for-big-data/\" target=\"_blank\">所说</a>：</p> <blockquote>\"...as information generating processes become more frictionless -- as humans have been excised from information read-write loops -- the velocity and volume of data in the world is increasing, and at an exponential rate... </blockquote> <p>“...当人们从读→写的信息循环中解脱出来，信息的产生变得更加没有阻碍。数据产生的速率和数量正在呈指数级增长...”</p> <blockquote>\"As the Big Data stack matures, tools that help manage the workflow from data to analytics to visualizations, and ultimately to decisions, will be critical. Someday, creating and sharing a data analysis through a web dashboard should be as easy as writing a blog post. Until that day, there's plenty of work to keep us data scientists well-employed.\"</blockquote> <p>“随着大数据集堆栈技术的成熟，工作流程（数据→分析→可视化→决策）的管理工具将更加精确。某一天，在网页界面制作和分享一份数据分析将如同写一篇博文般简单。到那时，我们的数据科学家就有得忙了。”</p> <blockquote>Or managing the data through automobile navigation, as the case may be. It's not hard to imagine new, self-driving automobiles competing in the market based on their navigation algorithms or the ways they enable human drivers to relate to all the rich data made available by sensors and cameras on cars.</blockquote> <p>或者通过汽车导航系统来管理数据，也许事情就是这样发展的——未来市场上的自动驾驶车将比拼着各自导航算法，或者驾驶者接触数据（产生自车上的传感器和摄像机）的用户体验。</p> <blockquote>Real-Time Data</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">实时数据：</span></p> <blockquote>The real-time Web has been mistakenly characterized as nothing but a stream of Tweets and Facebook updates.</blockquote> <p>实时网络居然被狭隘地定义为Tweets和Facebook上的一连串新鲜事。 </p> <blockquote>Just as real-time automated trading has changed the stock market forever, real-time delivery of big video and sensor data to and from the cloud and the car on street will change driving forever. </blockquote> <p>就像即使自动交易永久地改变了股票市场，街上的车辆与云端之间的大量视频和传感数据的实时推送，将永久地改变驾驶。</p> <blockquote>Accident avoidance is the most-obvious example, but there are others. Google spokespeople have talked about car-sharing programs that drive cars to the location of a would-be user on command, avoiding the inefficient use of valuable parking spaces in every neighborhood. Presumably those vehicles could predict where they are most likely to be needed, based on real-time data about existing behavior.</blockquote> <p>交通事故的避免是显而易见的，但不只如此。Google发言人还提及了一个分享使用汽车的程序，这个程序能指引汽车到达潜在的使用者身边，从而避免了占用社区中宝贵的停车空间。根据这位发言人的话推测，这样的车能够根据现有行为的实时数据，判断出它们最该到哪儿去载上一位乘客。</p> <blockquote>Ultimately, though, real-time will be most evident when you're in the car and it makes decisions based on surrounding circumstances as they unfold.</blockquote> <p>不过，最能体现“实时”的地方是当你坐在车上，看着汽车随着不断呈现的周边环境做出相应的决策时。</p> <blockquote>History</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">未来史：</span></p> <blockquote>The point is, trends like the Internet of Things, big data and real-time data are poised to impact the human experience in many different ways. Their convergence in the sci-fi scenario of self-driving cars is the example that will be most evident to everyday people.</blockquote> <p>我想要强调的是，物联网、大数据集以及实时技术等趋势将在很多方面深远地影响人类活动。最明显的例子就是科幻电影中那神奇的自动驾驶的汽车。</p> <blockquote>The consequences of such a technology on the psychology of autonomy, the ecology of transportation and urban planning and the million-plus lives lost every year due to human negligence behind the wheel, will be profound.</blockquote> <p>这些科技集合而成的汽车所带来的影响 意义深远，不管是对于自主权的心理学，运输系统的生态学而言，还是对于城市的规划，抑或是对于数以万计的在失去控制的车轮下消逝的生命而言。</p> <blockquote>Even more profound, though, will be the spread of these same technology trends throughout our lives. Beyond our cars, automation and real-time analysis of data-rich environments could change the human experience in many, many ways in the relatively near future.</blockquote> <p>更为深远的意义是，这些科技不光诞生了这样一辆车，它们将更近一步地渗透进我们生活的方方面面，在不远的将来，改变人类的生命体验。</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/134838/142465#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/166274/142270?from=rss_related\">MeeGo和Symbian——开源死到临头？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142081?from=rss_related\">Google将关闭自助语音查询服务GOOG-411</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/67213/142070?from=rss_related\">Google自动驾驶汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/153650/141988?from=rss_related\">为我们的学术研究创建Google自定义搜索</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/175538/141987?from=rss_related\">18款软件带你开启安智世界</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422809903/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/134838/142465\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422809903/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422809903/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>" "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/134838/142465" (19636 6602) old 2 nil nil ((title nil "Google自动驾驶车：千里之行，始于轮下") (link nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/134838/142465") (created ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T08:18:18+00:00") (issued ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T08:18:18+00:00") (modified ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T08:18:18+00:00") (id ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142465") (author ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) (name nil "tintinlock") (uri nil "http://space.yeeyan.org/u/134838")) (content ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom") (type . "html")) "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/googles_self-driving_car_where_it_stands_in_histor.php\">Google\\&#39;s Self-Driving Car is Just the Beginning</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/134838\">tintinlock</a></p><blockquote>Google announced this weekend that it has developed a car that can drive itself. A small fleet of the vehicles has logged more than 1,000 miles of entirely automated driving and 140,000 miles of driving with only occasional human intervention.</blockquote> <p>Google在本周宣布<a href=\"http://www.techmeme.com/101010/p21#a101010p21\" target=\"_blank\">它们研发了一款自动驾驶的汽车</a>。一小队这样的汽车已经全自动地行驶了1，000英里，另外在很少的人工干预下还行驶了140，000英里。</p> <blockquote>It's a development of historic significance: few events have changed the experience of life on earth as much as last century's proliferation of hundreds of millions of automobiles. The automobile was a revolution in personal autonomy, but it came with great costs. Now we've entered an era when that personal autonomy will become automated and some of the automobile's costs could be mitigated as a result. As a technologist, I find it helpful to understand the emergence of the fabled self-driving car as a convergence of three trends: the Internet of Things, Big Data and Real-Time Technology. Those trends are poised to go far beyond a self-driving car.</blockquote> <p>这是里程碑式的发展：上个世纪，汽车如雨后春笋般出现，深刻地改变了人类在地球上的生活，此后在没有什么事件能与之相提并论。个人自主权因为汽车的出现发生了变革，但同时代价是巨大的。不过，如今我们即将进入私人汽车的新时代——驾驶的完全自动化，以及因此减少的代价。作为一个技术专家，我觉得，为了更好地认识这种神话般的自动驾驶车的意义，我们可以将它视作三种趋势的集合：物联网，大数据集，以及实时科技。当然，这三者的发展绝不局限于自动驾驶车。</p> <blockquote>The Internet of Things</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">物联网：</span></p> <blockquote>The personal automobile was invented near the end of the 19th century and popularized throughout the 20th - approximately 600 million now traverse a world of roads. There is 1 car for every 11 people on earth, but sometimes it's hard to remember that - they can seem so ubiquitous. </blockquote> <p>私人汽车发明于19世纪末，流行于20世纪——大约有6亿辆车行驶在这个世界的路上。平均每11人才拥有一辆车——难以置信，它们明明无处不在。</p> <blockquote>As widespread and significant as they are, though, automobiles themselves have been to date relatively unconnected to each other. They are big, dumb, fast-moving hunks of metal. Essential, in fact, to keep apart from one another as they hurtle down the highway.</blockquote> <p>尽管汽车如此广泛和重要，它们仍然过时了——因为每一辆车都与其他的车不相往来，它们只是一块块默默赶路的金属。</p> <blockquote>\"Your car should drive itself,\" Google CEO Eric Schmidt foreshadowed in a public statement last week, days before the Google self-driving car was unveiled. \"It's amazing to me that we let humans drive cars. It's a bug that cars were invented before computers.\"</blockquote> <p>“你的车应该自己掌握方向盘，”Google的CEO Eric Schmidt在上周的一个<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/the_future_of_search_is_mobile_autonomous_serendipitous_says_google_ceo_eric_schmidt.php\" target=\"_blank\">公开声明</a>上如此预言——几天后Google发布了他们的自动驾驶车。“我不敢相信我们居然让人来开车。汽车在电脑之前被发明出来简直是个历史故障。”</p> <blockquote>The instrumentation and networking of previously offline objects, like cars, buildings, roads and more, may represent the next big stage in the evolution of technology. A network-connected car in particular - primarily navigated by artificial intelligence able to leverage a world of data hosted in the cloud - promises big gains in safety, efficiency and quality of life for everyday drivers.</blockquote> <p>科技革新的下一个舞台是把曾经与互联网分离的物品——汽车，建筑，公路等等——仪表化和联网化。以联网的汽车为例：存储在云端的数据恒河沙数，通过人工智能四两拨千斤，汽车便能由AI来导航。这种方式将带来安全性，效率和舒适度的巨大提升。</p> <blockquote>This product illustrates the potential for what's called the Internet of Things in a big way, but it should be understood in the context of the much larger trend. \"Trying to determine the market size of the Internet of Things is like trying to calculate the market for plastics, circa 1940,\" says Georgetown University Communication, Culture & Technology professor Michael Nelson, the former director of Internet Technology at IBM, and the former director of Technology Policy with the Federal Communications Commission, in a February report by The Hammersmith Group. \"At that time, it was difficult to imagine that plastics could be in every-thing. If you look at information processing in the same way, you begin to see the vast range of objects into which logic, processors, or actuators could be embedded.\"</blockquote> <p>这种汽车淋漓尽致地展示了物联网的美好图景，但我们还应将这个图景置于更大的时代背景中去看。“想要给物联网的市场规模下个定论，就像在1940年预测塑料的市场规模一样，”乔治敦大学文化与科技交流教授Michael Nelson在<a href=\"http://thehammersmithgroup.com/research.html\" target=\"_blank\">The Hammersmith Group</a>二月的一份报告中说。他曾是IBM互联网科技部的前任主管，联邦通讯委员会科技政策部门的前任主管。“那个时候（1940年），很难想象塑料会被用在各种物品上。如果你把现在的信息处理看作那时的塑料，那么你就能设想到逻辑处理器能被嵌入进多少东西。”</p> <blockquote>Big Data</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">大数据集：</span></p> <blockquote>How is Google able to drive a car? In part because its software has access to an incredible amount of very detailed data: maps of the world, speed limit information, live video of a car's surroundings, sharp computer vision analysis of what that live video contains and big-picture data about an emerging network of cars in motion on the road.</blockquote> <p>Google是如何让汽车自动驾驶的？部分原因在于，它的软件部分可以获得难以置信的详尽数据：世界地图，限速信息，周边环境的实时影像，清晰的可视化分析，以及由公路上汽车的动态所交织出的巨大网状图像。</p> <blockquote>Multiply that by not just one car, but countless cars throughout our roads and you've got a whole lot of data being processed. </blockquote> <p>这还仅仅是一辆车所能获得的信息，将它乘于汽车的总数——抱歉，这些车已经数不胜数了。想想你能得到多少信息吧。</p> <blockquote>Where there are network-connected devices, there are waves of data made available. Where there is big data, there are opportunities for pattern analysis, rational decisions and recommendations based on that data. </blockquote> <p>只要有联网设备，就有源源不断的数据产生。只要有大量数据，就不愁得不出图样分析，理性决策以及合理建议。</p> <blockquote>It's hard to know whether Google's self-driving cars ought to be called recommendation technology based on big data, or whether this is going beyond recommendation and into directive commands. </blockquote> <p>很难说Google的自动驾驶车应该被称为基于大数据集的推荐技术，还是它已经超越推荐技术，直接发号施令了。</p> <blockquote>Big data is, in large part, about decision making. A Google self-driving car will make it easier to make decisions about the important parts of driving by automating the parts that don't require human decision-making.</blockquote> <p>从很大范围来说，大数据集事关决策。一辆Google的自动驾驶车会让驾驶时进行重大决策变得更简单，因为它自动处理了不需要人类参与的决策部分。</p> <blockquote>As Michael E. Driscoll wrote this spring,</blockquote> <p>正如Michael E. Driscoll<a href=\"http://dataspora.com/blog/new-tools-for-big-data/\" target=\"_blank\">所说</a>：</p> <blockquote>\"...as information generating processes become more frictionless -- as humans have been excised from information read-write loops -- the velocity and volume of data in the world is increasing, and at an exponential rate... </blockquote> <p>“...当人们从读→写的信息循环中解脱出来，信息的产生变得更加没有阻碍。数据产生的速率和数量正在呈指数级增长...”</p> <blockquote>\"As the Big Data stack matures, tools that help manage the workflow from data to analytics to visualizations, and ultimately to decisions, will be critical. Someday, creating and sharing a data analysis through a web dashboard should be as easy as writing a blog post. Until that day, there's plenty of work to keep us data scientists well-employed.\"</blockquote> <p>“随着大数据集堆栈技术的成熟，工作流程（数据→分析→可视化→决策）的管理工具将更加精确。某一天，在网页界面制作和分享一份数据分析将如同写一篇博文般简单。到那时，我们的数据科学家就有得忙了。”</p> <blockquote>Or managing the data through automobile navigation, as the case may be. It's not hard to imagine new, self-driving automobiles competing in the market based on their navigation algorithms or the ways they enable human drivers to relate to all the rich data made available by sensors and cameras on cars.</blockquote> <p>或者通过汽车导航系统来管理数据，也许事情就是这样发展的——未来市场上的自动驾驶车将比拼着各自导航算法，或者驾驶者接触数据（产生自车上的传感器和摄像机）的用户体验。</p> <blockquote>Real-Time Data</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">实时数据：</span></p> <blockquote>The real-time Web has been mistakenly characterized as nothing but a stream of Tweets and Facebook updates.</blockquote> <p>实时网络居然被狭隘地定义为Tweets和Facebook上的一连串新鲜事。 </p> <blockquote>Just as real-time automated trading has changed the stock market forever, real-time delivery of big video and sensor data to and from the cloud and the car on street will change driving forever. </blockquote> <p>就像即使自动交易永久地改变了股票市场，街上的车辆与云端之间的大量视频和传感数据的实时推送，将永久地改变驾驶。</p> <blockquote>Accident avoidance is the most-obvious example, but there are others. Google spokespeople have talked about car-sharing programs that drive cars to the location of a would-be user on command, avoiding the inefficient use of valuable parking spaces in every neighborhood. Presumably those vehicles could predict where they are most likely to be needed, based on real-time data about existing behavior.</blockquote> <p>交通事故的避免是显而易见的，但不只如此。Google发言人还提及了一个分享使用汽车的程序，这个程序能指引汽车到达潜在的使用者身边，从而避免了占用社区中宝贵的停车空间。根据这位发言人的话推测，这样的车能够根据现有行为的实时数据，判断出它们最该到哪儿去载上一位乘客。</p> <blockquote>Ultimately, though, real-time will be most evident when you're in the car and it makes decisions based on surrounding circumstances as they unfold.</blockquote> <p>不过，最能体现“实时”的地方是当你坐在车上，看着汽车随着不断呈现的周边环境做出相应的决策时。</p> <blockquote>History</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">未来史：</span></p> <blockquote>The point is, trends like the Internet of Things, big data and real-time data are poised to impact the human experience in many different ways. Their convergence in the sci-fi scenario of self-driving cars is the example that will be most evident to everyday people.</blockquote> <p>我想要强调的是，物联网、大数据集以及实时技术等趋势将在很多方面深远地影响人类活动。最明显的例子就是科幻电影中那神奇的自动驾驶的汽车。</p> <blockquote>The consequences of such a technology on the psychology of autonomy, the ecology of transportation and urban planning and the million-plus lives lost every year due to human negligence behind the wheel, will be profound.</blockquote> <p>这些科技集合而成的汽车所带来的影响 意义深远，不管是对于自主权的心理学，运输系统的生态学而言，还是对于城市的规划，抑或是对于数以万计的在失去控制的车轮下消逝的生命而言。</p> <blockquote>Even more profound, though, will be the spread of these same technology trends throughout our lives. Beyond our cars, automation and real-time analysis of data-rich environments could change the human experience in many, many ways in the relatively near future.</blockquote> <p>更为深远的意义是，这些科技不光诞生了这样一辆车，它们将更近一步地渗透进我们生活的方方面面，在不远的将来，改变人类的生命体验。</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/134838/142465#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/166274/142270?from=rss_related\">MeeGo和Symbian——开源死到临头？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142081?from=rss_related\">Google将关闭自助语音查询服务GOOG-411</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/67213/142070?from=rss_related\">Google自动驾驶汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/153650/141988?from=rss_related\">为我们的学术研究创建Google自定义搜索</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/175538/141987?from=rss_related\">18款软件带你开启安智世界</a></p>") (content:encoded nil "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/googles_self-driving_car_where_it_stands_in_histor.php\">Google\\&#39;s Self-Driving Car is Just the Beginning</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/134838\">tintinlock</a></p><blockquote>Google announced this weekend that it has developed a car that can drive itself. A small fleet of the vehicles has logged more than 1,000 miles of entirely automated driving and 140,000 miles of driving with only occasional human intervention.</blockquote> <p>Google在本周宣布<a href=\"http://www.techmeme.com/101010/p21#a101010p21\" target=\"_blank\">它们研发了一款自动驾驶的汽车</a>。一小队这样的汽车已经全自动地行驶了1，000英里，另外在很少的人工干预下还行驶了140，000英里。</p> <blockquote>It's a development of historic significance: few events have changed the experience of life on earth as much as last century's proliferation of hundreds of millions of automobiles. The automobile was a revolution in personal autonomy, but it came with great costs. Now we've entered an era when that personal autonomy will become automated and some of the automobile's costs could be mitigated as a result. As a technologist, I find it helpful to understand the emergence of the fabled self-driving car as a convergence of three trends: the Internet of Things, Big Data and Real-Time Technology. Those trends are poised to go far beyond a self-driving car.</blockquote> <p>这是里程碑式的发展：上个世纪，汽车如雨后春笋般出现，深刻地改变了人类在地球上的生活，此后在没有什么事件能与之相提并论。个人自主权因为汽车的出现发生了变革，但同时代价是巨大的。不过，如今我们即将进入私人汽车的新时代——驾驶的完全自动化，以及因此减少的代价。作为一个技术专家，我觉得，为了更好地认识这种神话般的自动驾驶车的意义，我们可以将它视作三种趋势的集合：物联网，大数据集，以及实时科技。当然，这三者的发展绝不局限于自动驾驶车。</p> <blockquote>The Internet of Things</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">物联网：</span></p> <blockquote>The personal automobile was invented near the end of the 19th century and popularized throughout the 20th - approximately 600 million now traverse a world of roads. There is 1 car for every 11 people on earth, but sometimes it's hard to remember that - they can seem so ubiquitous. </blockquote> <p>私人汽车发明于19世纪末，流行于20世纪——大约有6亿辆车行驶在这个世界的路上。平均每11人才拥有一辆车——难以置信，它们明明无处不在。</p> <blockquote>As widespread and significant as they are, though, automobiles themselves have been to date relatively unconnected to each other. They are big, dumb, fast-moving hunks of metal. Essential, in fact, to keep apart from one another as they hurtle down the highway.</blockquote> <p>尽管汽车如此广泛和重要，它们仍然过时了——因为每一辆车都与其他的车不相往来，它们只是一块块默默赶路的金属。</p> <blockquote>\"Your car should drive itself,\" Google CEO Eric Schmidt foreshadowed in a public statement last week, days before the Google self-driving car was unveiled. \"It's amazing to me that we let humans drive cars. It's a bug that cars were invented before computers.\"</blockquote> <p>“你的车应该自己掌握方向盘，”Google的CEO Eric Schmidt在上周的一个<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/the_future_of_search_is_mobile_autonomous_serendipitous_says_google_ceo_eric_schmidt.php\" target=\"_blank\">公开声明</a>上如此预言——几天后Google发布了他们的自动驾驶车。“我不敢相信我们居然让人来开车。汽车在电脑之前被发明出来简直是个历史故障。”</p> <blockquote>The instrumentation and networking of previously offline objects, like cars, buildings, roads and more, may represent the next big stage in the evolution of technology. A network-connected car in particular - primarily navigated by artificial intelligence able to leverage a world of data hosted in the cloud - promises big gains in safety, efficiency and quality of life for everyday drivers.</blockquote> <p>科技革新的下一个舞台是把曾经与互联网分离的物品——汽车，建筑，公路等等——仪表化和联网化。以联网的汽车为例：存储在云端的数据恒河沙数，通过人工智能四两拨千斤，汽车便能由AI来导航。这种方式将带来安全性，效率和舒适度的巨大提升。</p> <blockquote>This product illustrates the potential for what's called the Internet of Things in a big way, but it should be understood in the context of the much larger trend. \"Trying to determine the market size of the Internet of Things is like trying to calculate the market for plastics, circa 1940,\" says Georgetown University Communication, Culture & Technology professor Michael Nelson, the former director of Internet Technology at IBM, and the former director of Technology Policy with the Federal Communications Commission, in a February report by The Hammersmith Group. \"At that time, it was difficult to imagine that plastics could be in every-thing. If you look at information processing in the same way, you begin to see the vast range of objects into which logic, processors, or actuators could be embedded.\"</blockquote> <p>这种汽车淋漓尽致地展示了物联网的美好图景，但我们还应将这个图景置于更大的时代背景中去看。“想要给物联网的市场规模下个定论，就像在1940年预测塑料的市场规模一样，”乔治敦大学文化与科技交流教授Michael Nelson在<a href=\"http://thehammersmithgroup.com/research.html\" target=\"_blank\">The Hammersmith Group</a>二月的一份报告中说。他曾是IBM互联网科技部的前任主管，联邦通讯委员会科技政策部门的前任主管。“那个时候（1940年），很难想象塑料会被用在各种物品上。如果你把现在的信息处理看作那时的塑料，那么你就能设想到逻辑处理器能被嵌入进多少东西。”</p> <blockquote>Big Data</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">大数据集：</span></p> <blockquote>How is Google able to drive a car? In part because its software has access to an incredible amount of very detailed data: maps of the world, speed limit information, live video of a car's surroundings, sharp computer vision analysis of what that live video contains and big-picture data about an emerging network of cars in motion on the road.</blockquote> <p>Google是如何让汽车自动驾驶的？部分原因在于，它的软件部分可以获得难以置信的详尽数据：世界地图，限速信息，周边环境的实时影像，清晰的可视化分析，以及由公路上汽车的动态所交织出的巨大网状图像。</p> <blockquote>Multiply that by not just one car, but countless cars throughout our roads and you've got a whole lot of data being processed. </blockquote> <p>这还仅仅是一辆车所能获得的信息，将它乘于汽车的总数——抱歉，这些车已经数不胜数了。想想你能得到多少信息吧。</p> <blockquote>Where there are network-connected devices, there are waves of data made available. Where there is big data, there are opportunities for pattern analysis, rational decisions and recommendations based on that data. </blockquote> <p>只要有联网设备，就有源源不断的数据产生。只要有大量数据，就不愁得不出图样分析，理性决策以及合理建议。</p> <blockquote>It's hard to know whether Google's self-driving cars ought to be called recommendation technology based on big data, or whether this is going beyond recommendation and into directive commands. </blockquote> <p>很难说Google的自动驾驶车应该被称为基于大数据集的推荐技术，还是它已经超越推荐技术，直接发号施令了。</p> <blockquote>Big data is, in large part, about decision making. A Google self-driving car will make it easier to make decisions about the important parts of driving by automating the parts that don't require human decision-making.</blockquote> <p>从很大范围来说，大数据集事关决策。一辆Google的自动驾驶车会让驾驶时进行重大决策变得更简单，因为它自动处理了不需要人类参与的决策部分。</p> <blockquote>As Michael E. Driscoll wrote this spring,</blockquote> <p>正如Michael E. Driscoll<a href=\"http://dataspora.com/blog/new-tools-for-big-data/\" target=\"_blank\">所说</a>：</p> <blockquote>\"...as information generating processes become more frictionless -- as humans have been excised from information read-write loops -- the velocity and volume of data in the world is increasing, and at an exponential rate... </blockquote> <p>“...当人们从读→写的信息循环中解脱出来，信息的产生变得更加没有阻碍。数据产生的速率和数量正在呈指数级增长...”</p> <blockquote>\"As the Big Data stack matures, tools that help manage the workflow from data to analytics to visualizations, and ultimately to decisions, will be critical. Someday, creating and sharing a data analysis through a web dashboard should be as easy as writing a blog post. Until that day, there's plenty of work to keep us data scientists well-employed.\"</blockquote> <p>“随着大数据集堆栈技术的成熟，工作流程（数据→分析→可视化→决策）的管理工具将更加精确。某一天，在网页界面制作和分享一份数据分析将如同写一篇博文般简单。到那时，我们的数据科学家就有得忙了。”</p> <blockquote>Or managing the data through automobile navigation, as the case may be. It's not hard to imagine new, self-driving automobiles competing in the market based on their navigation algorithms or the ways they enable human drivers to relate to all the rich data made available by sensors and cameras on cars.</blockquote> <p>或者通过汽车导航系统来管理数据，也许事情就是这样发展的——未来市场上的自动驾驶车将比拼着各自导航算法，或者驾驶者接触数据（产生自车上的传感器和摄像机）的用户体验。</p> <blockquote>Real-Time Data</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">实时数据：</span></p> <blockquote>The real-time Web has been mistakenly characterized as nothing but a stream of Tweets and Facebook updates.</blockquote> <p>实时网络居然被狭隘地定义为Tweets和Facebook上的一连串新鲜事。 </p> <blockquote>Just as real-time automated trading has changed the stock market forever, real-time delivery of big video and sensor data to and from the cloud and the car on street will change driving forever. </blockquote> <p>就像即使自动交易永久地改变了股票市场，街上的车辆与云端之间的大量视频和传感数据的实时推送，将永久地改变驾驶。</p> <blockquote>Accident avoidance is the most-obvious example, but there are others. Google spokespeople have talked about car-sharing programs that drive cars to the location of a would-be user on command, avoiding the inefficient use of valuable parking spaces in every neighborhood. Presumably those vehicles could predict where they are most likely to be needed, based on real-time data about existing behavior.</blockquote> <p>交通事故的避免是显而易见的，但不只如此。Google发言人还提及了一个分享使用汽车的程序，这个程序能指引汽车到达潜在的使用者身边，从而避免了占用社区中宝贵的停车空间。根据这位发言人的话推测，这样的车能够根据现有行为的实时数据，判断出它们最该到哪儿去载上一位乘客。</p> <blockquote>Ultimately, though, real-time will be most evident when you're in the car and it makes decisions based on surrounding circumstances as they unfold.</blockquote> <p>不过，最能体现“实时”的地方是当你坐在车上，看着汽车随着不断呈现的周边环境做出相应的决策时。</p> <blockquote>History</blockquote> <p><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">未来史：</span></p> <blockquote>The point is, trends like the Internet of Things, big data and real-time data are poised to impact the human experience in many different ways. Their convergence in the sci-fi scenario of self-driving cars is the example that will be most evident to everyday people.</blockquote> <p>我想要强调的是，物联网、大数据集以及实时技术等趋势将在很多方面深远地影响人类活动。最明显的例子就是科幻电影中那神奇的自动驾驶的汽车。</p> <blockquote>The consequences of such a technology on the psychology of autonomy, the ecology of transportation and urban planning and the million-plus lives lost every year due to human negligence behind the wheel, will be profound.</blockquote> <p>这些科技集合而成的汽车所带来的影响 意义深远，不管是对于自主权的心理学，运输系统的生态学而言，还是对于城市的规划，抑或是对于数以万计的在失去控制的车轮下消逝的生命而言。</p> <blockquote>Even more profound, though, will be the spread of these same technology trends throughout our lives. Beyond our cars, automation and real-time analysis of data-rich environments could change the human experience in many, many ways in the relatively near future.</blockquote> <p>更为深远的意义是，这些科技不光诞生了这样一辆车，它们将更近一步地渗透进我们生活的方方面面，在不远的将来，改变人类的生命体验。</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/134838/142465#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/166274/142270?from=rss_related\">MeeGo和Symbian——开源死到临头？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142081?from=rss_related\">Google将关闭自助语音查询服务GOOG-411</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/67213/142070?from=rss_related\">Google自动驾驶汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/153650/141988?from=rss_related\">为我们的学术研究创建Google自定义搜索</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/175538/141987?from=rss_related\">18款软件带你开启安智世界</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422809903/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/134838/142465\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422809903/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422809903/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>") (pubDate nil "Tue, 12 Oct 2010 16:18:18 +0800") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142465") (dc:creator nil "tintinlock") (fs:srclink nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/134838/142465") (fs:srcfeed nil "http://www.yeeyan.org/feed/category/410") (fs:itemid nil "feedsky/yeeyan-tech/~8024233/422809903/5032246"))) ("如何用Limera1n越狱iPhoone 4,3GS，iPod Touch和Apple TV" "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/mobile/2010/10/how-to-jailbreak-iphone-4-3gs-ipod-touch-and-appletv-with-limera1n.php\">How to Jailbreak the iPhone 4, 3GS, iPod Touch, and Apple TV with Limera1n</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/70506\">shirkeyyi</a></p><blockquote>This post is part of our ReadWriteMobile channel, which is dedicated to helping its community understand the strategic business and technical implications of developing mobile applications. This channel is sponsored by Alcatel-Lucent. As you're exploring these resources, check out this helpful resource from our sponsors: Cultivating a Developer Ecosystem: Understanding Their Needs</blockquote> <p>本篇文章是ReadWriteMobile频道的一部分，致力于帮助公众了解开发移动应用的战略业务和技术涵义。该频道由阿尔卡特朗讯赞助。查看这些资源时，请看一下这篇来自我们赞助商的有用资源：培育开发者生态系统：了解他们的需求。</p> <blockquote>Over the weekend, drama broke out in the iPhone hacking community. On the eve of the release of the new jailbreak tool for the latest version of the iPhone operating system - a tool called \"greenpois0n\" put out by a group of hackers called the \"Chronic Dev Team\" - another hacker swooped in and stole their glory. </blockquote> <p>周末，iPhone黑客社区发生了戏剧性的一幕。在越狱iPhone操作系统最新版本的工具发布前夕——自称\" Chronic Dev Team”的黑客推出的名为“greenpois0n”的工具，另一个黑客捷足先登并拿走了属于他们的荣耀。</p> <blockquote>An independent hacker known as \"geohot\" (aka George Hotz) pre-empted \"greenpois0n's\" launch by releasing his own tool called \"limera1n.\" (Don't you just love these names?) Here's what happened, how it impacts the jailbreak community, and yes, how to use limera1n to jailbreak your phone. </blockquote> <p>一个称“geohot”（又称乔治 霍茨）的独立黑客先发制人，在\"greenpois0n\"发布前发布了自己名为“limera1n\"的工具。（你能不喜欢这些名字吗？）事情是这样的：它是如何影响越狱社区的，恩，怎样使用limera1n软件越狱您的手机。</p> <blockquote>What Happened? Limera1n Trumps Greenpois0n</blockquote> <p>发生了什么？Limera1n胜过了Greenpoins0n</p> <blockquote>George Hotz is the hacker known best for his iPhone jailbreaking tools like purplera1n, blackra1n, blacksn0w, and perhaps more notably, for being the first to hack the Sony PS3. </blockquote> <p>乔治 霍茨是一位因其iPhone越狱工具而最为出名的黑客，如purplera1n, blackra1n和blacksn0w. 也许更为著名的是，他是第一位越狱索尼PS3的黑客。</p> <blockquote>His new jailbreak tool, continues the tradition of the \"ra1n\" naming scheme - it's called limera1n. But its release over the weekend was fraught with drama. </blockquote> <p>他新的越狱工具叫limera1n，延续了”ra1n“的命名传统。但其周末的发布却充满了戏剧性。</p> <blockquote>A group of iPhone hackers known as the Chronic Dev Team had prepared to launch their own jailbreak tool on 10/10/10, the one year anniversary of \"blackra1n.\" The tool, a software application called \"greenpois0n,\" was going to use a bootrom exploit they have dubbed \"SHAtter.\" Bootrom exploits are harder for Apple to patch because they take advantage of a vulnerability on the hardware level. Because of this, jailbreak tools using bootrom exploits are often referred to as tools that let you \"jailbreak for life.\" </blockquote> <p>一群称为Chronic Dev Team 的iPhone黑客准备在10年10月10号发布他们的越狱工具，而那天正好是”blackra1n\"发布一周年的日子。该工具是被称为“greenpois0n\"的软件应用程序，将使用名为”SHAtter“的bootrom漏洞利用。对Apple来说，bootrom漏洞很难修补，因为他们利用了硬件层面的弱点。正因为如此，使用bootrom漏洞利用的破解工具通常被称为”为生命而越狱“的工具。</p> <blockquote>The SHAtter exploit the Dev Team found was going to be used to jailbreak the iPhone, iPod Touch and iPad running the latest version of the iOS software. </blockquote> <p>Dev Team发现的SHAtter漏洞利用将被用来越狱iPhone，iPod Touch和使用iOS软件最新版本的iPad。</p> <blockquote>However, just prior to greenpois0n's launch, geohot returned with his own \"Limera1n\" jailbreak, which takes advantage of different vulnerability. Because the Chronic Dev Team does not want there to be two exploits in the wild at the same time (as Apple could then patch both at once), they've decided to withhold their SHAtter-based tool for now. Greenpois0n is now being delayed as they re-write it to use the same vulnerability as Limera1n. </blockquote> <p>然而，就在greenpois0n发布之前，geohot带着其“Limera1n”系统归来，该系统利用了另一个不同的弱点。由于Chronic Dev Team不希望两个漏洞利用同时出现（因为苹果可能一次性修补这两个漏洞），他们决定暂时停止其以SHAtter为基础的工具。现在，greenpois0n被暂缓，因为他们要重写软件，与Limera1n使用同一个弱点。</p> <blockquote>Jailbreaking with Limera1n: Jailbreak, But Unlockers Beware</blockquote> <p>用Limera1n软件越狱：越狱，但解锁者要当心</p> <blockquote>Jailbreaking and unlocking the iPhone are two different hacks which allow you to take control of your mobile device in different ways. Jailbreaking is a type of hack that lets you install unapproved third-party applications on your iPhone or iPod Touch from searchable repositories provided by apps like Cydia. Unlocking, on the other hand, is a hack that lets you use your iPhone on another cellular network. Here in the U.S., that means you can use the iPhone on T-Mobile instead of AT&T. You have to first jailbreak your phone before you can unlock it, but you don't have to unlock a phone in order to jailbreak it.</blockquote> <p>越狱和解锁是不同的，他们要求你用不同的方法来控制移动设备。越狱可以使你在iPhone或iPod Touch上安装第三方应用程序，这些程序并没有被应用程序所支持的可搜索的代码库如Cydia批准。而解锁可以让你的iPhone在另一个手机网络使用。在美国，解锁就意味着你可以在T-mobile而非AT&T使用iPhone。在解锁之前，你必须首先越狱你的手机。但要越狱手机并不需要先解锁。</p> <blockquote>There is a rumor that a \"limesn0w\" unlock from George Hotz is on its way, but that's unconfirmed at this time. A version of another tool called \"sn0wbreeze\" is also underway, which will offer support for unlockers. But for right now, the Dev Team is advising those using the current unlock called \"ultrasn0w\" to not not use Limera1n.</blockquote> <p>传言说乔治 霍茨的“limesn0w\"将要上市，但目前还没有得到证实。另一款叫做”sn0wbreeze\" 的工具也在进行当中，将给解锁者提供支持。但现在，Dev Team建议那些正在使用”ultrasn0w\"解锁系统的人一定不要使用Limera1n软件。</p> <blockquote>How to Jailbreak with Limera1n</blockquote> <p>怎么用Limera1n越狱</p> <blockquote>The new Limera1n jailbreak works on the iPhone3GS, iPhone4, iPod touch 3G, iPod touch 4G, the iPad, and (technically) the AppleTV 2G, although on the Apple TV there are no apps yet. It's a Windows-only tool, so there are no Mac or Linux instructions. However, a Mac version is coming soon. </blockquote> <p>虽然Apple TV还没有任何应用系统，但是新的Limera1n越狱软件可支持iPhone 3GS，iPhone 4，iPod touch 3G, iPod touch 4G, iPad和（从技术上讲）Apple TV 2G。它只是适用于Windows系统的工具，因此还没有Mac和Linux的越狱指导。然而，Mac版本的越狱软件即将推出。</p> <blockquote>Below is how to use Limera1n to jailbreak your device, tested by yours truly on the iPhone 4. </blockquote> <p>下边是怎样用Limera1n越狱您的设备，我在iPhone 4上亲自测试过。</p> <blockquote>Download the Windows software from limera1n.com. </blockquote> <p>从limera1n.com下载Windows软件</p> <blockquote>Connect your phone to your PC via USB. Close iTunes if it launches. </blockquote> <p>将手机通过USB连接到电脑上。关闭运行的iTunes。</p> <blockquote>Install the software (the limera1n.exe file). You'll need to click \"Run\" on the Windows Security Warning dialog box (Vista/Windows 7). </blockquote> <p>安装软件（limera1n.exe文件）。点击Windows安全警告对话框（Vista/Windows 7)中的“运行”按钮。</p> <blockquote>Click the \"make it ra1n\" button on the Window that appears. </blockquote> <p>点击所出现窗口中的“转为ra1n”按钮。</p> <blockquote>The window will first say \"waiting for device\" then \"entering recovery.\" It then prompts you to \"hold home + power\" (meaning, press both buttons at the same time). </blockquote> <p>窗口首先会显示“等待设备”，然后”进入复苏“。 然后它会提示你”按home+power键“（即同时按住两个键）。</p> <blockquote>You then release the \"power\" button when prompted by the software. If you mess up, it will tell you to retry. </blockquote> <p>然后，在软件提示时松开”power\"键。如果你做错了，它会提示你重试。</p> <blockquote>Windows finds and then installs the iPhone device driver - the message appears as a pop-up from the System Tray. The window now says \"entering DFU mode,\" \"exploiting\" and \"done.\" (iTunes launches in the background, but that's OK. ) </blockquote> <p>Windows会自动找到并安装iPhone设备驱动程序——系统托盘弹出时会显示信息。现在窗口显示“进入DFU模式”“运用”和“完成”。（iTunes在后台运行，但并不影响。）</p> <blockquote>A new message appears on the screen saying your jailbreak is ready. Click \"OK\" on this window. Close the other window too. </blockquote> <p>屏幕上出现一条新的信息，显示越狱已经完成。点击窗口的“确定“按钮，并关闭另一个窗口。</p> <blockquote>Reboot the device after seeing the limera1n raindrop icon on your phone's screen (press the power button to reboot). </blockquote> <p>在手机上看到limera1n雨滴图标后重新启动（按开关键重启）。</p> <blockquote>Once rebooted, you'll see the limera1n app on your device. Launch this app and on its main screen tap \"Cydia\" then the \"Install\" button at the top-right. </blockquote> <p>重启后，您可以在设备上看到limera1n应用程序。启动这个程序，并在其主界面点击”Cydia“，然后点击右上方的”安装“按钮。</p> <blockquote>Cydia will now download and install on your phone. This is the jailbreak app store.</blockquote> <p>现在Cydia会下载并安装在您手机上。这就是越狱应用程序商店。</p> <blockquote>Note: we found these instructions on Redmondpie.com and expanded upon them, incorporating things we encountered. Their site also offers video tutorials and device-specific guides, if needed.</blockquote> <p>注：我们在Redmondpie.com上发现了这些操作指南，并结合我们所遇到的问题对他们进行了补充。如果需要的话，他们的网站还提供视频教程和设备具体指导。</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/70506/142443#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142363?from=rss_related\">微软今天将推出Windows Phone 7</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/179408/141445?from=rss_related\">现在你的手机应用知道你在哪里了</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/129367/141023?from=rss_related\">【科学60秒】智能手机可能正在泄露你的隐私</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/178231/140638?from=rss_related\">你知道吗？关于手机和癌症的真相</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/178653/139354?from=rss_related\">为何手机对话让人如此心烦？</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422769562/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/70506/142443\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422769562/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422769562/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>" "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/70506/142443" (19636 3358) old 3 nil nil ((title nil "如何用Limera1n越狱iPhoone 4,3GS，iPod Touch和Apple TV") (link nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/70506/142443") (created ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T07:24:14+00:00") (issued ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T07:24:14+00:00") (modified ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T07:24:14+00:00") (id ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142443") (author ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) (name nil "shirkeyyi") (uri nil "http://space.yeeyan.org/u/70506")) (content ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom") (type . "html")) "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/mobile/2010/10/how-to-jailbreak-iphone-4-3gs-ipod-touch-and-appletv-with-limera1n.php\">How to Jailbreak the iPhone 4, 3GS, iPod Touch, and Apple TV with Limera1n</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/70506\">shirkeyyi</a></p><blockquote>This post is part of our ReadWriteMobile channel, which is dedicated to helping its community understand the strategic business and technical implications of developing mobile applications. This channel is sponsored by Alcatel-Lucent. As you're exploring these resources, check out this helpful resource from our sponsors: Cultivating a Developer Ecosystem: Understanding Their Needs</blockquote> <p>本篇文章是ReadWriteMobile频道的一部分，致力于帮助公众了解开发移动应用的战略业务和技术涵义。该频道由阿尔卡特朗讯赞助。查看这些资源时，请看一下这篇来自我们赞助商的有用资源：培育开发者生态系统：了解他们的需求。</p> <blockquote>Over the weekend, drama broke out in the iPhone hacking community. On the eve of the release of the new jailbreak tool for the latest version of the iPhone operating system - a tool called \"greenpois0n\" put out by a group of hackers called the \"Chronic Dev Team\" - another hacker swooped in and stole their glory. </blockquote> <p>周末，iPhone黑客社区发生了戏剧性的一幕。在越狱iPhone操作系统最新版本的工具发布前夕——自称\" Chronic Dev Team”的黑客推出的名为“greenpois0n”的工具，另一个黑客捷足先登并拿走了属于他们的荣耀。</p> <blockquote>An independent hacker known as \"geohot\" (aka George Hotz) pre-empted \"greenpois0n's\" launch by releasing his own tool called \"limera1n.\" (Don't you just love these names?) Here's what happened, how it impacts the jailbreak community, and yes, how to use limera1n to jailbreak your phone. </blockquote> <p>一个称“geohot”（又称乔治 霍茨）的独立黑客先发制人，在\"greenpois0n\"发布前发布了自己名为“limera1n\"的工具。（你能不喜欢这些名字吗？）事情是这样的：它是如何影响越狱社区的，恩，怎样使用limera1n软件越狱您的手机。</p> <blockquote>What Happened? Limera1n Trumps Greenpois0n</blockquote> <p>发生了什么？Limera1n胜过了Greenpoins0n</p> <blockquote>George Hotz is the hacker known best for his iPhone jailbreaking tools like purplera1n, blackra1n, blacksn0w, and perhaps more notably, for being the first to hack the Sony PS3. </blockquote> <p>乔治 霍茨是一位因其iPhone越狱工具而最为出名的黑客，如purplera1n, blackra1n和blacksn0w. 也许更为著名的是，他是第一位越狱索尼PS3的黑客。</p> <blockquote>His new jailbreak tool, continues the tradition of the \"ra1n\" naming scheme - it's called limera1n. But its release over the weekend was fraught with drama. </blockquote> <p>他新的越狱工具叫limera1n，延续了”ra1n“的命名传统。但其周末的发布却充满了戏剧性。</p> <blockquote>A group of iPhone hackers known as the Chronic Dev Team had prepared to launch their own jailbreak tool on 10/10/10, the one year anniversary of \"blackra1n.\" The tool, a software application called \"greenpois0n,\" was going to use a bootrom exploit they have dubbed \"SHAtter.\" Bootrom exploits are harder for Apple to patch because they take advantage of a vulnerability on the hardware level. Because of this, jailbreak tools using bootrom exploits are often referred to as tools that let you \"jailbreak for life.\" </blockquote> <p>一群称为Chronic Dev Team 的iPhone黑客准备在10年10月10号发布他们的越狱工具，而那天正好是”blackra1n\"发布一周年的日子。该工具是被称为“greenpois0n\"的软件应用程序，将使用名为”SHAtter“的bootrom漏洞利用。对Apple来说，bootrom漏洞很难修补，因为他们利用了硬件层面的弱点。正因为如此，使用bootrom漏洞利用的破解工具通常被称为”为生命而越狱“的工具。</p> <blockquote>The SHAtter exploit the Dev Team found was going to be used to jailbreak the iPhone, iPod Touch and iPad running the latest version of the iOS software. </blockquote> <p>Dev Team发现的SHAtter漏洞利用将被用来越狱iPhone，iPod Touch和使用iOS软件最新版本的iPad。</p> <blockquote>However, just prior to greenpois0n's launch, geohot returned with his own \"Limera1n\" jailbreak, which takes advantage of different vulnerability. Because the Chronic Dev Team does not want there to be two exploits in the wild at the same time (as Apple could then patch both at once), they've decided to withhold their SHAtter-based tool for now. Greenpois0n is now being delayed as they re-write it to use the same vulnerability as Limera1n. </blockquote> <p>然而，就在greenpois0n发布之前，geohot带着其“Limera1n”系统归来，该系统利用了另一个不同的弱点。由于Chronic Dev Team不希望两个漏洞利用同时出现（因为苹果可能一次性修补这两个漏洞），他们决定暂时停止其以SHAtter为基础的工具。现在，greenpois0n被暂缓，因为他们要重写软件，与Limera1n使用同一个弱点。</p> <blockquote>Jailbreaking with Limera1n: Jailbreak, But Unlockers Beware</blockquote> <p>用Limera1n软件越狱：越狱，但解锁者要当心</p> <blockquote>Jailbreaking and unlocking the iPhone are two different hacks which allow you to take control of your mobile device in different ways. Jailbreaking is a type of hack that lets you install unapproved third-party applications on your iPhone or iPod Touch from searchable repositories provided by apps like Cydia. Unlocking, on the other hand, is a hack that lets you use your iPhone on another cellular network. Here in the U.S., that means you can use the iPhone on T-Mobile instead of AT&T. You have to first jailbreak your phone before you can unlock it, but you don't have to unlock a phone in order to jailbreak it.</blockquote> <p>越狱和解锁是不同的，他们要求你用不同的方法来控制移动设备。越狱可以使你在iPhone或iPod Touch上安装第三方应用程序，这些程序并没有被应用程序所支持的可搜索的代码库如Cydia批准。而解锁可以让你的iPhone在另一个手机网络使用。在美国，解锁就意味着你可以在T-mobile而非AT&T使用iPhone。在解锁之前，你必须首先越狱你的手机。但要越狱手机并不需要先解锁。</p> <blockquote>There is a rumor that a \"limesn0w\" unlock from George Hotz is on its way, but that's unconfirmed at this time. A version of another tool called \"sn0wbreeze\" is also underway, which will offer support for unlockers. But for right now, the Dev Team is advising those using the current unlock called \"ultrasn0w\" to not not use Limera1n.</blockquote> <p>传言说乔治 霍茨的“limesn0w\"将要上市，但目前还没有得到证实。另一款叫做”sn0wbreeze\" 的工具也在进行当中，将给解锁者提供支持。但现在，Dev Team建议那些正在使用”ultrasn0w\"解锁系统的人一定不要使用Limera1n软件。</p> <blockquote>How to Jailbreak with Limera1n</blockquote> <p>怎么用Limera1n越狱</p> <blockquote>The new Limera1n jailbreak works on the iPhone3GS, iPhone4, iPod touch 3G, iPod touch 4G, the iPad, and (technically) the AppleTV 2G, although on the Apple TV there are no apps yet. It's a Windows-only tool, so there are no Mac or Linux instructions. However, a Mac version is coming soon. </blockquote> <p>虽然Apple TV还没有任何应用系统，但是新的Limera1n越狱软件可支持iPhone 3GS，iPhone 4，iPod touch 3G, iPod touch 4G, iPad和（从技术上讲）Apple TV 2G。它只是适用于Windows系统的工具，因此还没有Mac和Linux的越狱指导。然而，Mac版本的越狱软件即将推出。</p> <blockquote>Below is how to use Limera1n to jailbreak your device, tested by yours truly on the iPhone 4. </blockquote> <p>下边是怎样用Limera1n越狱您的设备，我在iPhone 4上亲自测试过。</p> <blockquote>Download the Windows software from limera1n.com. </blockquote> <p>从limera1n.com下载Windows软件</p> <blockquote>Connect your phone to your PC via USB. Close iTunes if it launches. </blockquote> <p>将手机通过USB连接到电脑上。关闭运行的iTunes。</p> <blockquote>Install the software (the limera1n.exe file). You'll need to click \"Run\" on the Windows Security Warning dialog box (Vista/Windows 7). </blockquote> <p>安装软件（limera1n.exe文件）。点击Windows安全警告对话框（Vista/Windows 7)中的“运行”按钮。</p> <blockquote>Click the \"make it ra1n\" button on the Window that appears. </blockquote> <p>点击所出现窗口中的“转为ra1n”按钮。</p> <blockquote>The window will first say \"waiting for device\" then \"entering recovery.\" It then prompts you to \"hold home + power\" (meaning, press both buttons at the same time). </blockquote> <p>窗口首先会显示“等待设备”，然后”进入复苏“。 然后它会提示你”按home+power键“（即同时按住两个键）。</p> <blockquote>You then release the \"power\" button when prompted by the software. If you mess up, it will tell you to retry. </blockquote> <p>然后，在软件提示时松开”power\"键。如果你做错了，它会提示你重试。</p> <blockquote>Windows finds and then installs the iPhone device driver - the message appears as a pop-up from the System Tray. The window now says \"entering DFU mode,\" \"exploiting\" and \"done.\" (iTunes launches in the background, but that's OK. ) </blockquote> <p>Windows会自动找到并安装iPhone设备驱动程序——系统托盘弹出时会显示信息。现在窗口显示“进入DFU模式”“运用”和“完成”。（iTunes在后台运行，但并不影响。）</p> <blockquote>A new message appears on the screen saying your jailbreak is ready. Click \"OK\" on this window. Close the other window too. </blockquote> <p>屏幕上出现一条新的信息，显示越狱已经完成。点击窗口的“确定“按钮，并关闭另一个窗口。</p> <blockquote>Reboot the device after seeing the limera1n raindrop icon on your phone's screen (press the power button to reboot). </blockquote> <p>在手机上看到limera1n雨滴图标后重新启动（按开关键重启）。</p> <blockquote>Once rebooted, you'll see the limera1n app on your device. Launch this app and on its main screen tap \"Cydia\" then the \"Install\" button at the top-right. </blockquote> <p>重启后，您可以在设备上看到limera1n应用程序。启动这个程序，并在其主界面点击”Cydia“，然后点击右上方的”安装“按钮。</p> <blockquote>Cydia will now download and install on your phone. This is the jailbreak app store.</blockquote> <p>现在Cydia会下载并安装在您手机上。这就是越狱应用程序商店。</p> <blockquote>Note: we found these instructions on Redmondpie.com and expanded upon them, incorporating things we encountered. Their site also offers video tutorials and device-specific guides, if needed.</blockquote> <p>注：我们在Redmondpie.com上发现了这些操作指南，并结合我们所遇到的问题对他们进行了补充。如果需要的话，他们的网站还提供视频教程和设备具体指导。</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/70506/142443#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142363?from=rss_related\">微软今天将推出Windows Phone 7</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/179408/141445?from=rss_related\">现在你的手机应用知道你在哪里了</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/129367/141023?from=rss_related\">【科学60秒】智能手机可能正在泄露你的隐私</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/178231/140638?from=rss_related\">你知道吗？关于手机和癌症的真相</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/178653/139354?from=rss_related\">为何手机对话让人如此心烦？</a></p>") (content:encoded nil "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/mobile/2010/10/how-to-jailbreak-iphone-4-3gs-ipod-touch-and-appletv-with-limera1n.php\">How to Jailbreak the iPhone 4, 3GS, iPod Touch, and Apple TV with Limera1n</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/70506\">shirkeyyi</a></p><blockquote>This post is part of our ReadWriteMobile channel, which is dedicated to helping its community understand the strategic business and technical implications of developing mobile applications. This channel is sponsored by Alcatel-Lucent. As you're exploring these resources, check out this helpful resource from our sponsors: Cultivating a Developer Ecosystem: Understanding Their Needs</blockquote> <p>本篇文章是ReadWriteMobile频道的一部分，致力于帮助公众了解开发移动应用的战略业务和技术涵义。该频道由阿尔卡特朗讯赞助。查看这些资源时，请看一下这篇来自我们赞助商的有用资源：培育开发者生态系统：了解他们的需求。</p> <blockquote>Over the weekend, drama broke out in the iPhone hacking community. On the eve of the release of the new jailbreak tool for the latest version of the iPhone operating system - a tool called \"greenpois0n\" put out by a group of hackers called the \"Chronic Dev Team\" - another hacker swooped in and stole their glory. </blockquote> <p>周末，iPhone黑客社区发生了戏剧性的一幕。在越狱iPhone操作系统最新版本的工具发布前夕——自称\" Chronic Dev Team”的黑客推出的名为“greenpois0n”的工具，另一个黑客捷足先登并拿走了属于他们的荣耀。</p> <blockquote>An independent hacker known as \"geohot\" (aka George Hotz) pre-empted \"greenpois0n's\" launch by releasing his own tool called \"limera1n.\" (Don't you just love these names?) Here's what happened, how it impacts the jailbreak community, and yes, how to use limera1n to jailbreak your phone. </blockquote> <p>一个称“geohot”（又称乔治 霍茨）的独立黑客先发制人，在\"greenpois0n\"发布前发布了自己名为“limera1n\"的工具。（你能不喜欢这些名字吗？）事情是这样的：它是如何影响越狱社区的，恩，怎样使用limera1n软件越狱您的手机。</p> <blockquote>What Happened? Limera1n Trumps Greenpois0n</blockquote> <p>发生了什么？Limera1n胜过了Greenpoins0n</p> <blockquote>George Hotz is the hacker known best for his iPhone jailbreaking tools like purplera1n, blackra1n, blacksn0w, and perhaps more notably, for being the first to hack the Sony PS3. </blockquote> <p>乔治 霍茨是一位因其iPhone越狱工具而最为出名的黑客，如purplera1n, blackra1n和blacksn0w. 也许更为著名的是，他是第一位越狱索尼PS3的黑客。</p> <blockquote>His new jailbreak tool, continues the tradition of the \"ra1n\" naming scheme - it's called limera1n. But its release over the weekend was fraught with drama. </blockquote> <p>他新的越狱工具叫limera1n，延续了”ra1n“的命名传统。但其周末的发布却充满了戏剧性。</p> <blockquote>A group of iPhone hackers known as the Chronic Dev Team had prepared to launch their own jailbreak tool on 10/10/10, the one year anniversary of \"blackra1n.\" The tool, a software application called \"greenpois0n,\" was going to use a bootrom exploit they have dubbed \"SHAtter.\" Bootrom exploits are harder for Apple to patch because they take advantage of a vulnerability on the hardware level. Because of this, jailbreak tools using bootrom exploits are often referred to as tools that let you \"jailbreak for life.\" </blockquote> <p>一群称为Chronic Dev Team 的iPhone黑客准备在10年10月10号发布他们的越狱工具，而那天正好是”blackra1n\"发布一周年的日子。该工具是被称为“greenpois0n\"的软件应用程序，将使用名为”SHAtter“的bootrom漏洞利用。对Apple来说，bootrom漏洞很难修补，因为他们利用了硬件层面的弱点。正因为如此，使用bootrom漏洞利用的破解工具通常被称为”为生命而越狱“的工具。</p> <blockquote>The SHAtter exploit the Dev Team found was going to be used to jailbreak the iPhone, iPod Touch and iPad running the latest version of the iOS software. </blockquote> <p>Dev Team发现的SHAtter漏洞利用将被用来越狱iPhone，iPod Touch和使用iOS软件最新版本的iPad。</p> <blockquote>However, just prior to greenpois0n's launch, geohot returned with his own \"Limera1n\" jailbreak, which takes advantage of different vulnerability. Because the Chronic Dev Team does not want there to be two exploits in the wild at the same time (as Apple could then patch both at once), they've decided to withhold their SHAtter-based tool for now. Greenpois0n is now being delayed as they re-write it to use the same vulnerability as Limera1n. </blockquote> <p>然而，就在greenpois0n发布之前，geohot带着其“Limera1n”系统归来，该系统利用了另一个不同的弱点。由于Chronic Dev Team不希望两个漏洞利用同时出现（因为苹果可能一次性修补这两个漏洞），他们决定暂时停止其以SHAtter为基础的工具。现在，greenpois0n被暂缓，因为他们要重写软件，与Limera1n使用同一个弱点。</p> <blockquote>Jailbreaking with Limera1n: Jailbreak, But Unlockers Beware</blockquote> <p>用Limera1n软件越狱：越狱，但解锁者要当心</p> <blockquote>Jailbreaking and unlocking the iPhone are two different hacks which allow you to take control of your mobile device in different ways. Jailbreaking is a type of hack that lets you install unapproved third-party applications on your iPhone or iPod Touch from searchable repositories provided by apps like Cydia. Unlocking, on the other hand, is a hack that lets you use your iPhone on another cellular network. Here in the U.S., that means you can use the iPhone on T-Mobile instead of AT&T. You have to first jailbreak your phone before you can unlock it, but you don't have to unlock a phone in order to jailbreak it.</blockquote> <p>越狱和解锁是不同的，他们要求你用不同的方法来控制移动设备。越狱可以使你在iPhone或iPod Touch上安装第三方应用程序，这些程序并没有被应用程序所支持的可搜索的代码库如Cydia批准。而解锁可以让你的iPhone在另一个手机网络使用。在美国，解锁就意味着你可以在T-mobile而非AT&T使用iPhone。在解锁之前，你必须首先越狱你的手机。但要越狱手机并不需要先解锁。</p> <blockquote>There is a rumor that a \"limesn0w\" unlock from George Hotz is on its way, but that's unconfirmed at this time. A version of another tool called \"sn0wbreeze\" is also underway, which will offer support for unlockers. But for right now, the Dev Team is advising those using the current unlock called \"ultrasn0w\" to not not use Limera1n.</blockquote> <p>传言说乔治 霍茨的“limesn0w\"将要上市，但目前还没有得到证实。另一款叫做”sn0wbreeze\" 的工具也在进行当中，将给解锁者提供支持。但现在，Dev Team建议那些正在使用”ultrasn0w\"解锁系统的人一定不要使用Limera1n软件。</p> <blockquote>How to Jailbreak with Limera1n</blockquote> <p>怎么用Limera1n越狱</p> <blockquote>The new Limera1n jailbreak works on the iPhone3GS, iPhone4, iPod touch 3G, iPod touch 4G, the iPad, and (technically) the AppleTV 2G, although on the Apple TV there are no apps yet. It's a Windows-only tool, so there are no Mac or Linux instructions. However, a Mac version is coming soon. </blockquote> <p>虽然Apple TV还没有任何应用系统，但是新的Limera1n越狱软件可支持iPhone 3GS，iPhone 4，iPod touch 3G, iPod touch 4G, iPad和（从技术上讲）Apple TV 2G。它只是适用于Windows系统的工具，因此还没有Mac和Linux的越狱指导。然而，Mac版本的越狱软件即将推出。</p> <blockquote>Below is how to use Limera1n to jailbreak your device, tested by yours truly on the iPhone 4. </blockquote> <p>下边是怎样用Limera1n越狱您的设备，我在iPhone 4上亲自测试过。</p> <blockquote>Download the Windows software from limera1n.com. </blockquote> <p>从limera1n.com下载Windows软件</p> <blockquote>Connect your phone to your PC via USB. Close iTunes if it launches. </blockquote> <p>将手机通过USB连接到电脑上。关闭运行的iTunes。</p> <blockquote>Install the software (the limera1n.exe file). You'll need to click \"Run\" on the Windows Security Warning dialog box (Vista/Windows 7). </blockquote> <p>安装软件（limera1n.exe文件）。点击Windows安全警告对话框（Vista/Windows 7)中的“运行”按钮。</p> <blockquote>Click the \"make it ra1n\" button on the Window that appears. </blockquote> <p>点击所出现窗口中的“转为ra1n”按钮。</p> <blockquote>The window will first say \"waiting for device\" then \"entering recovery.\" It then prompts you to \"hold home + power\" (meaning, press both buttons at the same time). </blockquote> <p>窗口首先会显示“等待设备”，然后”进入复苏“。 然后它会提示你”按home+power键“（即同时按住两个键）。</p> <blockquote>You then release the \"power\" button when prompted by the software. If you mess up, it will tell you to retry. </blockquote> <p>然后，在软件提示时松开”power\"键。如果你做错了，它会提示你重试。</p> <blockquote>Windows finds and then installs the iPhone device driver - the message appears as a pop-up from the System Tray. The window now says \"entering DFU mode,\" \"exploiting\" and \"done.\" (iTunes launches in the background, but that's OK. ) </blockquote> <p>Windows会自动找到并安装iPhone设备驱动程序——系统托盘弹出时会显示信息。现在窗口显示“进入DFU模式”“运用”和“完成”。（iTunes在后台运行，但并不影响。）</p> <blockquote>A new message appears on the screen saying your jailbreak is ready. Click \"OK\" on this window. Close the other window too. </blockquote> <p>屏幕上出现一条新的信息，显示越狱已经完成。点击窗口的“确定“按钮，并关闭另一个窗口。</p> <blockquote>Reboot the device after seeing the limera1n raindrop icon on your phone's screen (press the power button to reboot). </blockquote> <p>在手机上看到limera1n雨滴图标后重新启动（按开关键重启）。</p> <blockquote>Once rebooted, you'll see the limera1n app on your device. Launch this app and on its main screen tap \"Cydia\" then the \"Install\" button at the top-right. </blockquote> <p>重启后，您可以在设备上看到limera1n应用程序。启动这个程序，并在其主界面点击”Cydia“，然后点击右上方的”安装“按钮。</p> <blockquote>Cydia will now download and install on your phone. This is the jailbreak app store.</blockquote> <p>现在Cydia会下载并安装在您手机上。这就是越狱应用程序商店。</p> <blockquote>Note: we found these instructions on Redmondpie.com and expanded upon them, incorporating things we encountered. Their site also offers video tutorials and device-specific guides, if needed.</blockquote> <p>注：我们在Redmondpie.com上发现了这些操作指南，并结合我们所遇到的问题对他们进行了补充。如果需要的话，他们的网站还提供视频教程和设备具体指导。</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/70506/142443#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/pestwave/142363?from=rss_related\">微软今天将推出Windows Phone 7</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/179408/141445?from=rss_related\">现在你的手机应用知道你在哪里了</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/129367/141023?from=rss_related\">【科学60秒】智能手机可能正在泄露你的隐私</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/178231/140638?from=rss_related\">你知道吗？关于手机和癌症的真相</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/178653/139354?from=rss_related\">为何手机对话让人如此心烦？</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422769562/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/70506/142443\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422769562/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422769562/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>") (pubDate nil "Tue, 12 Oct 2010 15:24:14 +0800") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142443") (dc:creator nil "shirkeyyi") (fs:srclink nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/70506/142443") (fs:srcfeed nil "http://www.yeeyan.org/feed/category/410") (fs:itemid nil "feedsky/yeeyan-tech/~8024233/422769562/5032246"))) ("自动行驶的谷歌汽车——超乎你的想象" "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/10/science/10google.html?_r=1&amp;ref=science\">Smarter Than You Think - Google Cars Drive Themselves, in Traffic - NYTimescom</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/105279\">jays</a></p><blockquote>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. — Anyone driving the twists of Highway 1 between San Francisco and Los Angeles recently may have glimpsed a Toyota Prius with a curious funnel-like cylinder on the roof. Harder to notice was that the person at the wheel was not actually driving.</blockquote> <p><span style=\"line-height:21px;\"><img src=\"http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2010/10/10/us/10google-span/10google-span-articleLarge.jpg\" /></span></p> <p>加州山景城——最近在旧金山和洛杉矶之间蜿蜒的 1 号高速公路上路过的人们可能会看到一辆车顶带有一个奇怪的烟囱似的圆筒的丰田普锐斯车。就算你看到这辆车，你也不一定能注意到方向盘前的那个人其实并没有在驾驶。</p> <blockquote>The car is a project of Google, which has been working in secret but in plain view on vehicles that can drive themselves, using artificial-intelligence software that can sense anything near the car and mimic the decisions made by a human driver.</blockquote> <p>这辆车是谷歌的一个秘密进行的项目，不过随着实体车的出现而进入人们的视野，它通过人工智能的软件感应任何在车辆附近的物体，模拟人类驾驶员对此作出的决定来自动驾驶汽车。</p> <blockquote>With someone behind the wheel to take control if something goes awry and a technician in the passenger seat to monitor the navigation system, seven test cars have driven 1,000 miles without human intervention and more than 140,000 miles with only occasional human control. One even drove itself down Lombard Street in San Francisco, one of the steepest and curviest streets in the nation. The only accident, engineers said, was when one Google car was rear-ended while stopped at a traffic light.</blockquote> <p>7 辆测试车上各配有两名测试人员，驾驶位置上的人在车子走歪的时候稍作调整，而乘客位置上的技术人员对导航系统进行监控，这些车已经在无人干涉的情况下行驶了 1 千英里、在偶尔人工干预的情况下行驶了 14 万英里。有一辆甚至自动行驶在旧金山这条全国最陡最曲折的伦巴帝街上。工程师称，唯一一次事故是一辆谷歌车在等绿灯时被追尾。</p> <blockquote>Autonomous cars are years from mass production, but technologists who have long dreamed of them believe that they can transform society as profoundly as the Internet has.</blockquote> <p>自动汽车离大规模生产还有许多年的路要走，不过对此憧憬了多年的技术人员相信自动汽车可以像因特网一样改变这个社会。</p> <blockquote>Robot drivers react faster than humans, have 360-degree perception and do not get distracted, sleepy or intoxicated, the engineers argue. They speak in terms of lives saved and injuries avoided — more than 37,000 people died in car accidents in the United States in 2008. The engineers say the technology could double the capacity of roads by allowing cars to drive more safely while closer together. Because the robot cars would eventually be less likely to crash, they could be built lighter, reducing fuel consumption. But of course, to be truly safer, the cars must be far more reliable than, say, today’s personal computers, which crash on occasion and are frequently infected.</blockquote> <p>工程师们提出，机器人司机比人类的反应更快、有着 360 度的感知能力、不会分心、瞌睡或者喝醉。他们以可以避免的伤亡人数来说明问题——在 2008 年的美国，有 3 万 7 千人死于车祸。工程师们称这一技术可以让汽车之间即使保持更近的距离也能更安全地行驶，从而加倍公路运载量。因为机器人汽车最终将不容易发生撞车事故，所以它们可以造得更轻、油耗更少。不过当然，要想真正地安全，汽车必须比如今时常崩溃、经常中毒的个人电脑更加可靠。</p> <blockquote>The Google research program using artificial intelligence to revolutionize the automobile is proof that the company’s ambitions reach beyond the search engine business. The program is also a departure from the mainstream of innovation in Silicon Valley, which has veered toward social networks and Hollywood-style digital media.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的这一利用人工智能改革汽车的研究项目证明了该公司在搜索引擎业务之外的雄心。该项目同样在硅谷现在转向社交网络和好莱坞式的数字媒体的主流革新中也是异军突起。</p> <blockquote>During a half-hour drive beginning on Google’s campus 35 miles south of San Francisco last Wednesday, a Prius equipped with a variety of sensors and following a route programmed into the GPS navigation system nimbly accelerated in the entrance lane and merged into fast-moving traffic on Highway 101, the freeway through Silicon Valley.</blockquote> <p>在上周四于旧金山以南 35 英里的谷歌园地发车的历时半小时的行驶过程中，一辆装备有各种传感器的普锐斯跟随者 GPS 导航系统绘制的路线敏捷地加速驶入上匝道口，进入 101 号这条穿过硅谷的高速公路川流不息的车流中。</p> <blockquote>It drove at the speed limit, which it knew because the limit for every road is included in its database, and left the freeway several exits later. The device atop the car produced a detailed map of the environment.</blockquote> <p>它以限速行驶，因为它的数据库中存有每一条路的限速，在几个下匝道口之后离开了高速公路。在车顶上的设备可以生成周围环境的详细地图。</p> <blockquote>The car then drove in city traffic through Mountain View, stopping for lights and stop signs, as well as making announcements like “approaching a crosswalk” (to warn the human at the wheel) or “turn ahead” in a pleasant female voice. This same pleasant voice would, engineers said, alert the driver if a master control system detected anything amiss with the various sensors.</blockquote> <p>这辆车接着驶入山景城的城市车流中，遇到红灯就停，还会用柔美的女声发出类似“接近斑马线”或者“前面转弯”的提示（用以提醒驾驶员）。工程师称，如果主控制系统检测到各种传感器中出现了毛病，这个声音也会响起，提醒驾驶员。</p> <blockquote>The car can be programmed for different driving personalities — from cautious, in which it is more likely to yield to another car, to aggressive, where it is more likely to go first.</blockquote> <p>这辆车可以为不同的驾驶习惯进行程序设置——从谨慎的到蛮横的，前者更容易选择避让其他的车辆，后者倾向于抢先。</p> <blockquote>Christopher Urmson, a Carnegie Mellon University robotics scientist, was behind the wheel but not using it. To gain control of the car he has to do one of three things: hit a red button near his right hand, touch the brake or turn the steering wheel. He did so twice, once when a bicyclist ran a red light and again when a car in front stopped and began to back into a parking space. But the car seemed likely to have prevented an accident itself.</blockquote> <p>卡内基梅隆大学的机械学家克里斯多佛·厄姆森坐在方向盘后面，但并没有在驾驶。他必须做下面三件事中的一种来得到车辆的控制权：按下右手边的红色按钮、踩刹车或者转方向盘。这种情况发生了两次，一次是有个骑自行车的闯红灯，另一次是一辆前车突然停车倒入车位。不过这辆车似乎很可能自己就能避免事故的发生。</p> <blockquote>When he returned to automated “cruise” mode, the car gave a little “whir” meant to evoke going into warp drive on “Star Trek,” and Dr. Urmson was able to rest his hands by his sides or gesticulate when talking to a passenger in the back seat. He said the cars did attract attention, but people seem to think they are just the next generation of the Street View cars that Google uses to take photographs and collect data for its maps.</blockquote> <p>当他回到自动“巡航”模式，这辆车会发出轻微的“呜呜”声，让人想到《星际迷航》里进入空间跳跃的声音，此时厄姆森博士就可以在和后座的乘客交谈时将双手放在座位两边，或者比划手势了。他说这些车确实会吸引人们的注意，不过人们似乎认为它们只是谷歌用于拍摄照片收集地图数据的新一代的街景小车。</p> <blockquote>The project is the brainchild of Sebastian Thrun, the 43-year-old director of the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, a Google engineer and the co-inventor of the Street View mapping service.</blockquote> <p>这个项目是 43 岁的斯坦福人工智能实验室主任、谷歌工程师、街景地图服务的合作发明者塞巴斯蒂安·特隆的点子。</p> <blockquote>In 2005, he led a team of Stanford students and faculty members in designing the Stanley robot car, winning the second Grand Challenge of the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, a $2 million Pentagon prize for driving autonomously over 132 miles in the desert.</blockquote> <p>在 2005 年，他带领了一支斯坦福大学生和专业人士组成的团队设计了名叫斯坦利的自动汽车，获得了美国国防部高级计划研究局大挑战赛的二等奖，五角大楼授予他们发明的能在沙漠中自动行驶 132 英里的汽车 2 百万美元的奖金。</p> <blockquote>Besides the team of 15 engineers working on the current project, Google hired more than a dozen people, each with a spotless driving record, to sit in the driver’s seat, paying $15 an hour or more. Google is using six Priuses and an Audi TT in the project.</blockquote> <p>除了这支正进行当前项目的 15 名工程师组成的小队以外，谷歌还雇用了数十名员工，他们个个都有着完美的驾车记录，让他们坐在驾驶位置上，每小时佣金为 15 美元甚至更高。谷歌在这个项目中使用了 6 台普锐斯和一台奥迪 TT。</p> <blockquote>The Google researchers said the company did not yet have a clear plan to create a business from the experiments. Dr. Thrun is known as a passionate promoter of the potential to use robotic vehicles to make highways safer and lower the nation’s energy costs. It is a commitment shared by Larry Page, Google’s co-founder, according to several people familiar with the project.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的研究人员称他们的公司目前还没有根据这些试验确定明确的商业计划。特隆博士是有名的热衷于推广利用自动车辆以改善高速公路安全性、降低国家的能源消耗的潜力的人士。据熟悉该项目的一些人表示，谷歌的合作创始人拉里·佩奇也抱有相同的看法。</p> <blockquote>The self-driving car initiative is an example of Google’s willingness to gamble on technology that may not pay off for years, Dr. Thrun said. Even the most optimistic predictions put the deployment of the technology more than eight years away.</blockquote> <p>特隆博士说，自动驾驶汽车的倡导是个很好的例子，表现了谷歌想要将赌注押在短期可能无法收益的技术上的想法。就算是最乐观的预测也认为这一技术的运用将在超过 8 年以后才能实现。</p> <blockquote>One way Google might be able to profit is to provide information and navigation services for makers of autonomous vehicles. Or, it might sell or give away the navigation technology itself, much as it offers its Android smart phone system to cellphone companies.</blockquote> <p>谷歌可能用以获利的一种方式是为自动汽车制造商提供信息和导航服务。或者，它可能会自行销售或者分配导航技术，这就像它为手机公司提供 Android 智能手机系统那样。</p> <blockquote>But the advent of autonomous vehicles poses thorny legal issues, the Google researchers acknowledged. Under current law, a human must be in control of a car at all times, but what does that mean if the human is not really paying attention as the car crosses through, say, a school zone, figuring that the robot is driving more safely than he would?</blockquote> <p>不过，谷歌的研究人员知道，自动车辆的出现也造成了许多麻烦的法律问题。在目前的法律下，必须有人一直控制着汽车，但如果在穿越例如学校区域时，驾驶员并没有真正地集中注意力，而认为机器人能比他更安全地驾驶汽车，这又该如何处理呢？</p> <blockquote>And in the event of an accident, who would be liable — the person behind the wheel or the maker of the software?</blockquote> <p>而在发生事故时，谁又该负法律责任呢——是驾驶员还是软件制造商呢？</p> <blockquote>“The technology is ahead of the law in many areas,” said Bernard Lu, senior staff counsel for the California Department of Motor Vehicles. “If you look at the vehicle code, there are dozens of laws pertaining to the driver of a vehicle, and they all presume to have a human being operating the vehicle.”</blockquote> <p>“这项技术在很多方面都超前于法律，”加州机动车部的高级律师伯纳德·陆表示，“如果你读一读车辆法规，会发现几十条有关车辆驾驶员的条例，它们都以有个人在驾驶车辆为前提。”</p> <blockquote>The Google researchers said they had carefully examined California’s motor vehicle regulations and determined that because a human driver can override any error, the experimental cars are legal. Mr. Lu agreed.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的研究人员称他们仔细研究了加州的机动车条例，认定因为驾驶员可以纠正任何错误的发生，所以试验车是合法的。而陆先生也表示同意。</p> <blockquote>Scientists and engineers have been designing autonomous vehicles since the mid-1960s, but crucial innovation happened in 2004 when the Pentagon’s research arm began its Grand Challenge.</blockquote> <p>科学家和工程师们从 20 世纪 60 年代中叶就开始设计自动车辆了，但到了 2004 年五角大楼研究机构发起大挑战赛时才迎来了关键性的革新。</p> <blockquote>The first contest ended in failure, but in 2005, Dr. Thrun’s Stanford team built the car that won a race with a rival vehicle built by a team from Carnegie Mellon University. Less than two years later, another event proved that autonomous vehicles could drive safely in urban settings.</blockquote> <p>第一次大赛以失败告终，但到了 2005 年，特隆博士的斯坦福团队制造的汽车在和竞争对手卡内基梅隆大学的汽车的比赛中获胜。不到两年以后，另一次活动再次证明了自动车辆能够在城市道路设置中安全行驶。</p> <blockquote>Advances have been so encouraging that Dr. Thrun sounds like an evangelist when he speaks of robot cars. There is their potential to reduce fuel consumption by eliminating heavy-footed stop-and-go drivers and, given the reduced possibility of accidents, to ultimately build more lightweight vehicles.</blockquote> <p>研究进展如此令人振奋，以至于特隆博士在谈到自动汽车时语气好似布道。他们有潜力通过摒弃大力的刹车和加速来减少油耗，并减少事故的可能性，最终创造出更加轻量级的车辆。</p> <blockquote>There is even the farther-off prospect of cars that do not need anyone behind the wheel. That would allow the cars to be summoned electronically, so that people could share them. Fewer cars would then be needed, reducing the need for parking spaces, which consume valuable land.</blockquote> <p>他们甚至构想了更进一步的不需要驾驶员的车辆概念。这能够让汽车通过电子通信方式随叫随到，这样一来人们就可以共享车辆了。这样就不需要这么多的车辆，还能减少停车的空间占用，节约出宝贵的土地。</p> <blockquote>And, of course, the cars could save humans from themselves. “Can we text twice as much while driving, without the guilt?” Dr. Thrun said in a recent talk. “Yes, we can, if only cars will drive themselves.”</blockquote> <p>而且，这些车当然可以解放人力。“我们能毫无负罪感地在驾车时发更多的短信息吗？”特隆博士在最近的一次谈话中说，“没错，我们可以这么做，只要汽车能够自动行驶。”</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/105279/142401#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/166284/142361?from=rss_related\">谷歌竟也玩起了汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180478/142155?from=rss_related\">汽车声音的未来</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/153650/141988?from=rss_related\">为我们的学术研究创建Google自定义搜索</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180619/141919?from=rss_related\">道路上的谷歌无人驾驶汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180619/141910?from=rss_related\">谷歌成功测试无人驾驶汽车</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422733068/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/105279/142401\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733068/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733068/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>" "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/105279/142401" (19635 61224) old 4 nil nil ((title nil "自动行驶的谷歌汽车——超乎你的想象") (link nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/105279/142401") (created ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T05:16:24+00:00") (issued ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T05:16:24+00:00") (modified ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T05:16:24+00:00") (id ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142401") (author ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) (name nil "jays") (uri nil "http://space.yeeyan.org/u/105279")) (content ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom") (type . "html")) "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/10/science/10google.html?_r=1&amp;ref=science\">Smarter Than You Think - Google Cars Drive Themselves, in Traffic - NYTimescom</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/105279\">jays</a></p><blockquote>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. — Anyone driving the twists of Highway 1 between San Francisco and Los Angeles recently may have glimpsed a Toyota Prius with a curious funnel-like cylinder on the roof. Harder to notice was that the person at the wheel was not actually driving.</blockquote> <p><span style=\"line-height:21px;\"><img src=\"http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2010/10/10/us/10google-span/10google-span-articleLarge.jpg\" /></span></p> <p>加州山景城——最近在旧金山和洛杉矶之间蜿蜒的 1 号高速公路上路过的人们可能会看到一辆车顶带有一个奇怪的烟囱似的圆筒的丰田普锐斯车。就算你看到这辆车，你也不一定能注意到方向盘前的那个人其实并没有在驾驶。</p> <blockquote>The car is a project of Google, which has been working in secret but in plain view on vehicles that can drive themselves, using artificial-intelligence software that can sense anything near the car and mimic the decisions made by a human driver.</blockquote> <p>这辆车是谷歌的一个秘密进行的项目，不过随着实体车的出现而进入人们的视野，它通过人工智能的软件感应任何在车辆附近的物体，模拟人类驾驶员对此作出的决定来自动驾驶汽车。</p> <blockquote>With someone behind the wheel to take control if something goes awry and a technician in the passenger seat to monitor the navigation system, seven test cars have driven 1,000 miles without human intervention and more than 140,000 miles with only occasional human control. One even drove itself down Lombard Street in San Francisco, one of the steepest and curviest streets in the nation. The only accident, engineers said, was when one Google car was rear-ended while stopped at a traffic light.</blockquote> <p>7 辆测试车上各配有两名测试人员，驾驶位置上的人在车子走歪的时候稍作调整，而乘客位置上的技术人员对导航系统进行监控，这些车已经在无人干涉的情况下行驶了 1 千英里、在偶尔人工干预的情况下行驶了 14 万英里。有一辆甚至自动行驶在旧金山这条全国最陡最曲折的伦巴帝街上。工程师称，唯一一次事故是一辆谷歌车在等绿灯时被追尾。</p> <blockquote>Autonomous cars are years from mass production, but technologists who have long dreamed of them believe that they can transform society as profoundly as the Internet has.</blockquote> <p>自动汽车离大规模生产还有许多年的路要走，不过对此憧憬了多年的技术人员相信自动汽车可以像因特网一样改变这个社会。</p> <blockquote>Robot drivers react faster than humans, have 360-degree perception and do not get distracted, sleepy or intoxicated, the engineers argue. They speak in terms of lives saved and injuries avoided — more than 37,000 people died in car accidents in the United States in 2008. The engineers say the technology could double the capacity of roads by allowing cars to drive more safely while closer together. Because the robot cars would eventually be less likely to crash, they could be built lighter, reducing fuel consumption. But of course, to be truly safer, the cars must be far more reliable than, say, today’s personal computers, which crash on occasion and are frequently infected.</blockquote> <p>工程师们提出，机器人司机比人类的反应更快、有着 360 度的感知能力、不会分心、瞌睡或者喝醉。他们以可以避免的伤亡人数来说明问题——在 2008 年的美国，有 3 万 7 千人死于车祸。工程师们称这一技术可以让汽车之间即使保持更近的距离也能更安全地行驶，从而加倍公路运载量。因为机器人汽车最终将不容易发生撞车事故，所以它们可以造得更轻、油耗更少。不过当然，要想真正地安全，汽车必须比如今时常崩溃、经常中毒的个人电脑更加可靠。</p> <blockquote>The Google research program using artificial intelligence to revolutionize the automobile is proof that the company’s ambitions reach beyond the search engine business. The program is also a departure from the mainstream of innovation in Silicon Valley, which has veered toward social networks and Hollywood-style digital media.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的这一利用人工智能改革汽车的研究项目证明了该公司在搜索引擎业务之外的雄心。该项目同样在硅谷现在转向社交网络和好莱坞式的数字媒体的主流革新中也是异军突起。</p> <blockquote>During a half-hour drive beginning on Google’s campus 35 miles south of San Francisco last Wednesday, a Prius equipped with a variety of sensors and following a route programmed into the GPS navigation system nimbly accelerated in the entrance lane and merged into fast-moving traffic on Highway 101, the freeway through Silicon Valley.</blockquote> <p>在上周四于旧金山以南 35 英里的谷歌园地发车的历时半小时的行驶过程中，一辆装备有各种传感器的普锐斯跟随者 GPS 导航系统绘制的路线敏捷地加速驶入上匝道口，进入 101 号这条穿过硅谷的高速公路川流不息的车流中。</p> <blockquote>It drove at the speed limit, which it knew because the limit for every road is included in its database, and left the freeway several exits later. The device atop the car produced a detailed map of the environment.</blockquote> <p>它以限速行驶，因为它的数据库中存有每一条路的限速，在几个下匝道口之后离开了高速公路。在车顶上的设备可以生成周围环境的详细地图。</p> <blockquote>The car then drove in city traffic through Mountain View, stopping for lights and stop signs, as well as making announcements like “approaching a crosswalk” (to warn the human at the wheel) or “turn ahead” in a pleasant female voice. This same pleasant voice would, engineers said, alert the driver if a master control system detected anything amiss with the various sensors.</blockquote> <p>这辆车接着驶入山景城的城市车流中，遇到红灯就停，还会用柔美的女声发出类似“接近斑马线”或者“前面转弯”的提示（用以提醒驾驶员）。工程师称，如果主控制系统检测到各种传感器中出现了毛病，这个声音也会响起，提醒驾驶员。</p> <blockquote>The car can be programmed for different driving personalities — from cautious, in which it is more likely to yield to another car, to aggressive, where it is more likely to go first.</blockquote> <p>这辆车可以为不同的驾驶习惯进行程序设置——从谨慎的到蛮横的，前者更容易选择避让其他的车辆，后者倾向于抢先。</p> <blockquote>Christopher Urmson, a Carnegie Mellon University robotics scientist, was behind the wheel but not using it. To gain control of the car he has to do one of three things: hit a red button near his right hand, touch the brake or turn the steering wheel. He did so twice, once when a bicyclist ran a red light and again when a car in front stopped and began to back into a parking space. But the car seemed likely to have prevented an accident itself.</blockquote> <p>卡内基梅隆大学的机械学家克里斯多佛·厄姆森坐在方向盘后面，但并没有在驾驶。他必须做下面三件事中的一种来得到车辆的控制权：按下右手边的红色按钮、踩刹车或者转方向盘。这种情况发生了两次，一次是有个骑自行车的闯红灯，另一次是一辆前车突然停车倒入车位。不过这辆车似乎很可能自己就能避免事故的发生。</p> <blockquote>When he returned to automated “cruise” mode, the car gave a little “whir” meant to evoke going into warp drive on “Star Trek,” and Dr. Urmson was able to rest his hands by his sides or gesticulate when talking to a passenger in the back seat. He said the cars did attract attention, but people seem to think they are just the next generation of the Street View cars that Google uses to take photographs and collect data for its maps.</blockquote> <p>当他回到自动“巡航”模式，这辆车会发出轻微的“呜呜”声，让人想到《星际迷航》里进入空间跳跃的声音，此时厄姆森博士就可以在和后座的乘客交谈时将双手放在座位两边，或者比划手势了。他说这些车确实会吸引人们的注意，不过人们似乎认为它们只是谷歌用于拍摄照片收集地图数据的新一代的街景小车。</p> <blockquote>The project is the brainchild of Sebastian Thrun, the 43-year-old director of the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, a Google engineer and the co-inventor of the Street View mapping service.</blockquote> <p>这个项目是 43 岁的斯坦福人工智能实验室主任、谷歌工程师、街景地图服务的合作发明者塞巴斯蒂安·特隆的点子。</p> <blockquote>In 2005, he led a team of Stanford students and faculty members in designing the Stanley robot car, winning the second Grand Challenge of the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, a $2 million Pentagon prize for driving autonomously over 132 miles in the desert.</blockquote> <p>在 2005 年，他带领了一支斯坦福大学生和专业人士组成的团队设计了名叫斯坦利的自动汽车，获得了美国国防部高级计划研究局大挑战赛的二等奖，五角大楼授予他们发明的能在沙漠中自动行驶 132 英里的汽车 2 百万美元的奖金。</p> <blockquote>Besides the team of 15 engineers working on the current project, Google hired more than a dozen people, each with a spotless driving record, to sit in the driver’s seat, paying $15 an hour or more. Google is using six Priuses and an Audi TT in the project.</blockquote> <p>除了这支正进行当前项目的 15 名工程师组成的小队以外，谷歌还雇用了数十名员工，他们个个都有着完美的驾车记录，让他们坐在驾驶位置上，每小时佣金为 15 美元甚至更高。谷歌在这个项目中使用了 6 台普锐斯和一台奥迪 TT。</p> <blockquote>The Google researchers said the company did not yet have a clear plan to create a business from the experiments. Dr. Thrun is known as a passionate promoter of the potential to use robotic vehicles to make highways safer and lower the nation’s energy costs. It is a commitment shared by Larry Page, Google’s co-founder, according to several people familiar with the project.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的研究人员称他们的公司目前还没有根据这些试验确定明确的商业计划。特隆博士是有名的热衷于推广利用自动车辆以改善高速公路安全性、降低国家的能源消耗的潜力的人士。据熟悉该项目的一些人表示，谷歌的合作创始人拉里·佩奇也抱有相同的看法。</p> <blockquote>The self-driving car initiative is an example of Google’s willingness to gamble on technology that may not pay off for years, Dr. Thrun said. Even the most optimistic predictions put the deployment of the technology more than eight years away.</blockquote> <p>特隆博士说，自动驾驶汽车的倡导是个很好的例子，表现了谷歌想要将赌注押在短期可能无法收益的技术上的想法。就算是最乐观的预测也认为这一技术的运用将在超过 8 年以后才能实现。</p> <blockquote>One way Google might be able to profit is to provide information and navigation services for makers of autonomous vehicles. Or, it might sell or give away the navigation technology itself, much as it offers its Android smart phone system to cellphone companies.</blockquote> <p>谷歌可能用以获利的一种方式是为自动汽车制造商提供信息和导航服务。或者，它可能会自行销售或者分配导航技术，这就像它为手机公司提供 Android 智能手机系统那样。</p> <blockquote>But the advent of autonomous vehicles poses thorny legal issues, the Google researchers acknowledged. Under current law, a human must be in control of a car at all times, but what does that mean if the human is not really paying attention as the car crosses through, say, a school zone, figuring that the robot is driving more safely than he would?</blockquote> <p>不过，谷歌的研究人员知道，自动车辆的出现也造成了许多麻烦的法律问题。在目前的法律下，必须有人一直控制着汽车，但如果在穿越例如学校区域时，驾驶员并没有真正地集中注意力，而认为机器人能比他更安全地驾驶汽车，这又该如何处理呢？</p> <blockquote>And in the event of an accident, who would be liable — the person behind the wheel or the maker of the software?</blockquote> <p>而在发生事故时，谁又该负法律责任呢——是驾驶员还是软件制造商呢？</p> <blockquote>“The technology is ahead of the law in many areas,” said Bernard Lu, senior staff counsel for the California Department of Motor Vehicles. “If you look at the vehicle code, there are dozens of laws pertaining to the driver of a vehicle, and they all presume to have a human being operating the vehicle.”</blockquote> <p>“这项技术在很多方面都超前于法律，”加州机动车部的高级律师伯纳德·陆表示，“如果你读一读车辆法规，会发现几十条有关车辆驾驶员的条例，它们都以有个人在驾驶车辆为前提。”</p> <blockquote>The Google researchers said they had carefully examined California’s motor vehicle regulations and determined that because a human driver can override any error, the experimental cars are legal. Mr. Lu agreed.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的研究人员称他们仔细研究了加州的机动车条例，认定因为驾驶员可以纠正任何错误的发生，所以试验车是合法的。而陆先生也表示同意。</p> <blockquote>Scientists and engineers have been designing autonomous vehicles since the mid-1960s, but crucial innovation happened in 2004 when the Pentagon’s research arm began its Grand Challenge.</blockquote> <p>科学家和工程师们从 20 世纪 60 年代中叶就开始设计自动车辆了，但到了 2004 年五角大楼研究机构发起大挑战赛时才迎来了关键性的革新。</p> <blockquote>The first contest ended in failure, but in 2005, Dr. Thrun’s Stanford team built the car that won a race with a rival vehicle built by a team from Carnegie Mellon University. Less than two years later, another event proved that autonomous vehicles could drive safely in urban settings.</blockquote> <p>第一次大赛以失败告终，但到了 2005 年，特隆博士的斯坦福团队制造的汽车在和竞争对手卡内基梅隆大学的汽车的比赛中获胜。不到两年以后，另一次活动再次证明了自动车辆能够在城市道路设置中安全行驶。</p> <blockquote>Advances have been so encouraging that Dr. Thrun sounds like an evangelist when he speaks of robot cars. There is their potential to reduce fuel consumption by eliminating heavy-footed stop-and-go drivers and, given the reduced possibility of accidents, to ultimately build more lightweight vehicles.</blockquote> <p>研究进展如此令人振奋，以至于特隆博士在谈到自动汽车时语气好似布道。他们有潜力通过摒弃大力的刹车和加速来减少油耗，并减少事故的可能性，最终创造出更加轻量级的车辆。</p> <blockquote>There is even the farther-off prospect of cars that do not need anyone behind the wheel. That would allow the cars to be summoned electronically, so that people could share them. Fewer cars would then be needed, reducing the need for parking spaces, which consume valuable land.</blockquote> <p>他们甚至构想了更进一步的不需要驾驶员的车辆概念。这能够让汽车通过电子通信方式随叫随到，这样一来人们就可以共享车辆了。这样就不需要这么多的车辆，还能减少停车的空间占用，节约出宝贵的土地。</p> <blockquote>And, of course, the cars could save humans from themselves. “Can we text twice as much while driving, without the guilt?” Dr. Thrun said in a recent talk. “Yes, we can, if only cars will drive themselves.”</blockquote> <p>而且，这些车当然可以解放人力。“我们能毫无负罪感地在驾车时发更多的短信息吗？”特隆博士在最近的一次谈话中说，“没错，我们可以这么做，只要汽车能够自动行驶。”</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/105279/142401#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/166284/142361?from=rss_related\">谷歌竟也玩起了汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180478/142155?from=rss_related\">汽车声音的未来</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/153650/141988?from=rss_related\">为我们的学术研究创建Google自定义搜索</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180619/141919?from=rss_related\">道路上的谷歌无人驾驶汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180619/141910?from=rss_related\">谷歌成功测试无人驾驶汽车</a></p>") (content:encoded nil "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/10/science/10google.html?_r=1&amp;ref=science\">Smarter Than You Think - Google Cars Drive Themselves, in Traffic - NYTimescom</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/105279\">jays</a></p><blockquote>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. — Anyone driving the twists of Highway 1 between San Francisco and Los Angeles recently may have glimpsed a Toyota Prius with a curious funnel-like cylinder on the roof. Harder to notice was that the person at the wheel was not actually driving.</blockquote> <p><span style=\"line-height:21px;\"><img src=\"http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2010/10/10/us/10google-span/10google-span-articleLarge.jpg\" /></span></p> <p>加州山景城——最近在旧金山和洛杉矶之间蜿蜒的 1 号高速公路上路过的人们可能会看到一辆车顶带有一个奇怪的烟囱似的圆筒的丰田普锐斯车。就算你看到这辆车，你也不一定能注意到方向盘前的那个人其实并没有在驾驶。</p> <blockquote>The car is a project of Google, which has been working in secret but in plain view on vehicles that can drive themselves, using artificial-intelligence software that can sense anything near the car and mimic the decisions made by a human driver.</blockquote> <p>这辆车是谷歌的一个秘密进行的项目，不过随着实体车的出现而进入人们的视野，它通过人工智能的软件感应任何在车辆附近的物体，模拟人类驾驶员对此作出的决定来自动驾驶汽车。</p> <blockquote>With someone behind the wheel to take control if something goes awry and a technician in the passenger seat to monitor the navigation system, seven test cars have driven 1,000 miles without human intervention and more than 140,000 miles with only occasional human control. One even drove itself down Lombard Street in San Francisco, one of the steepest and curviest streets in the nation. The only accident, engineers said, was when one Google car was rear-ended while stopped at a traffic light.</blockquote> <p>7 辆测试车上各配有两名测试人员，驾驶位置上的人在车子走歪的时候稍作调整，而乘客位置上的技术人员对导航系统进行监控，这些车已经在无人干涉的情况下行驶了 1 千英里、在偶尔人工干预的情况下行驶了 14 万英里。有一辆甚至自动行驶在旧金山这条全国最陡最曲折的伦巴帝街上。工程师称，唯一一次事故是一辆谷歌车在等绿灯时被追尾。</p> <blockquote>Autonomous cars are years from mass production, but technologists who have long dreamed of them believe that they can transform society as profoundly as the Internet has.</blockquote> <p>自动汽车离大规模生产还有许多年的路要走，不过对此憧憬了多年的技术人员相信自动汽车可以像因特网一样改变这个社会。</p> <blockquote>Robot drivers react faster than humans, have 360-degree perception and do not get distracted, sleepy or intoxicated, the engineers argue. They speak in terms of lives saved and injuries avoided — more than 37,000 people died in car accidents in the United States in 2008. The engineers say the technology could double the capacity of roads by allowing cars to drive more safely while closer together. Because the robot cars would eventually be less likely to crash, they could be built lighter, reducing fuel consumption. But of course, to be truly safer, the cars must be far more reliable than, say, today’s personal computers, which crash on occasion and are frequently infected.</blockquote> <p>工程师们提出，机器人司机比人类的反应更快、有着 360 度的感知能力、不会分心、瞌睡或者喝醉。他们以可以避免的伤亡人数来说明问题——在 2008 年的美国，有 3 万 7 千人死于车祸。工程师们称这一技术可以让汽车之间即使保持更近的距离也能更安全地行驶，从而加倍公路运载量。因为机器人汽车最终将不容易发生撞车事故，所以它们可以造得更轻、油耗更少。不过当然，要想真正地安全，汽车必须比如今时常崩溃、经常中毒的个人电脑更加可靠。</p> <blockquote>The Google research program using artificial intelligence to revolutionize the automobile is proof that the company’s ambitions reach beyond the search engine business. The program is also a departure from the mainstream of innovation in Silicon Valley, which has veered toward social networks and Hollywood-style digital media.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的这一利用人工智能改革汽车的研究项目证明了该公司在搜索引擎业务之外的雄心。该项目同样在硅谷现在转向社交网络和好莱坞式的数字媒体的主流革新中也是异军突起。</p> <blockquote>During a half-hour drive beginning on Google’s campus 35 miles south of San Francisco last Wednesday, a Prius equipped with a variety of sensors and following a route programmed into the GPS navigation system nimbly accelerated in the entrance lane and merged into fast-moving traffic on Highway 101, the freeway through Silicon Valley.</blockquote> <p>在上周四于旧金山以南 35 英里的谷歌园地发车的历时半小时的行驶过程中，一辆装备有各种传感器的普锐斯跟随者 GPS 导航系统绘制的路线敏捷地加速驶入上匝道口，进入 101 号这条穿过硅谷的高速公路川流不息的车流中。</p> <blockquote>It drove at the speed limit, which it knew because the limit for every road is included in its database, and left the freeway several exits later. The device atop the car produced a detailed map of the environment.</blockquote> <p>它以限速行驶，因为它的数据库中存有每一条路的限速，在几个下匝道口之后离开了高速公路。在车顶上的设备可以生成周围环境的详细地图。</p> <blockquote>The car then drove in city traffic through Mountain View, stopping for lights and stop signs, as well as making announcements like “approaching a crosswalk” (to warn the human at the wheel) or “turn ahead” in a pleasant female voice. This same pleasant voice would, engineers said, alert the driver if a master control system detected anything amiss with the various sensors.</blockquote> <p>这辆车接着驶入山景城的城市车流中，遇到红灯就停，还会用柔美的女声发出类似“接近斑马线”或者“前面转弯”的提示（用以提醒驾驶员）。工程师称，如果主控制系统检测到各种传感器中出现了毛病，这个声音也会响起，提醒驾驶员。</p> <blockquote>The car can be programmed for different driving personalities — from cautious, in which it is more likely to yield to another car, to aggressive, where it is more likely to go first.</blockquote> <p>这辆车可以为不同的驾驶习惯进行程序设置——从谨慎的到蛮横的，前者更容易选择避让其他的车辆，后者倾向于抢先。</p> <blockquote>Christopher Urmson, a Carnegie Mellon University robotics scientist, was behind the wheel but not using it. To gain control of the car he has to do one of three things: hit a red button near his right hand, touch the brake or turn the steering wheel. He did so twice, once when a bicyclist ran a red light and again when a car in front stopped and began to back into a parking space. But the car seemed likely to have prevented an accident itself.</blockquote> <p>卡内基梅隆大学的机械学家克里斯多佛·厄姆森坐在方向盘后面，但并没有在驾驶。他必须做下面三件事中的一种来得到车辆的控制权：按下右手边的红色按钮、踩刹车或者转方向盘。这种情况发生了两次，一次是有个骑自行车的闯红灯，另一次是一辆前车突然停车倒入车位。不过这辆车似乎很可能自己就能避免事故的发生。</p> <blockquote>When he returned to automated “cruise” mode, the car gave a little “whir” meant to evoke going into warp drive on “Star Trek,” and Dr. Urmson was able to rest his hands by his sides or gesticulate when talking to a passenger in the back seat. He said the cars did attract attention, but people seem to think they are just the next generation of the Street View cars that Google uses to take photographs and collect data for its maps.</blockquote> <p>当他回到自动“巡航”模式，这辆车会发出轻微的“呜呜”声，让人想到《星际迷航》里进入空间跳跃的声音，此时厄姆森博士就可以在和后座的乘客交谈时将双手放在座位两边，或者比划手势了。他说这些车确实会吸引人们的注意，不过人们似乎认为它们只是谷歌用于拍摄照片收集地图数据的新一代的街景小车。</p> <blockquote>The project is the brainchild of Sebastian Thrun, the 43-year-old director of the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, a Google engineer and the co-inventor of the Street View mapping service.</blockquote> <p>这个项目是 43 岁的斯坦福人工智能实验室主任、谷歌工程师、街景地图服务的合作发明者塞巴斯蒂安·特隆的点子。</p> <blockquote>In 2005, he led a team of Stanford students and faculty members in designing the Stanley robot car, winning the second Grand Challenge of the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, a $2 million Pentagon prize for driving autonomously over 132 miles in the desert.</blockquote> <p>在 2005 年，他带领了一支斯坦福大学生和专业人士组成的团队设计了名叫斯坦利的自动汽车，获得了美国国防部高级计划研究局大挑战赛的二等奖，五角大楼授予他们发明的能在沙漠中自动行驶 132 英里的汽车 2 百万美元的奖金。</p> <blockquote>Besides the team of 15 engineers working on the current project, Google hired more than a dozen people, each with a spotless driving record, to sit in the driver’s seat, paying $15 an hour or more. Google is using six Priuses and an Audi TT in the project.</blockquote> <p>除了这支正进行当前项目的 15 名工程师组成的小队以外，谷歌还雇用了数十名员工，他们个个都有着完美的驾车记录，让他们坐在驾驶位置上，每小时佣金为 15 美元甚至更高。谷歌在这个项目中使用了 6 台普锐斯和一台奥迪 TT。</p> <blockquote>The Google researchers said the company did not yet have a clear plan to create a business from the experiments. Dr. Thrun is known as a passionate promoter of the potential to use robotic vehicles to make highways safer and lower the nation’s energy costs. It is a commitment shared by Larry Page, Google’s co-founder, according to several people familiar with the project.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的研究人员称他们的公司目前还没有根据这些试验确定明确的商业计划。特隆博士是有名的热衷于推广利用自动车辆以改善高速公路安全性、降低国家的能源消耗的潜力的人士。据熟悉该项目的一些人表示，谷歌的合作创始人拉里·佩奇也抱有相同的看法。</p> <blockquote>The self-driving car initiative is an example of Google’s willingness to gamble on technology that may not pay off for years, Dr. Thrun said. Even the most optimistic predictions put the deployment of the technology more than eight years away.</blockquote> <p>特隆博士说，自动驾驶汽车的倡导是个很好的例子，表现了谷歌想要将赌注押在短期可能无法收益的技术上的想法。就算是最乐观的预测也认为这一技术的运用将在超过 8 年以后才能实现。</p> <blockquote>One way Google might be able to profit is to provide information and navigation services for makers of autonomous vehicles. Or, it might sell or give away the navigation technology itself, much as it offers its Android smart phone system to cellphone companies.</blockquote> <p>谷歌可能用以获利的一种方式是为自动汽车制造商提供信息和导航服务。或者，它可能会自行销售或者分配导航技术，这就像它为手机公司提供 Android 智能手机系统那样。</p> <blockquote>But the advent of autonomous vehicles poses thorny legal issues, the Google researchers acknowledged. Under current law, a human must be in control of a car at all times, but what does that mean if the human is not really paying attention as the car crosses through, say, a school zone, figuring that the robot is driving more safely than he would?</blockquote> <p>不过，谷歌的研究人员知道，自动车辆的出现也造成了许多麻烦的法律问题。在目前的法律下，必须有人一直控制着汽车，但如果在穿越例如学校区域时，驾驶员并没有真正地集中注意力，而认为机器人能比他更安全地驾驶汽车，这又该如何处理呢？</p> <blockquote>And in the event of an accident, who would be liable — the person behind the wheel or the maker of the software?</blockquote> <p>而在发生事故时，谁又该负法律责任呢——是驾驶员还是软件制造商呢？</p> <blockquote>“The technology is ahead of the law in many areas,” said Bernard Lu, senior staff counsel for the California Department of Motor Vehicles. “If you look at the vehicle code, there are dozens of laws pertaining to the driver of a vehicle, and they all presume to have a human being operating the vehicle.”</blockquote> <p>“这项技术在很多方面都超前于法律，”加州机动车部的高级律师伯纳德·陆表示，“如果你读一读车辆法规，会发现几十条有关车辆驾驶员的条例，它们都以有个人在驾驶车辆为前提。”</p> <blockquote>The Google researchers said they had carefully examined California’s motor vehicle regulations and determined that because a human driver can override any error, the experimental cars are legal. Mr. Lu agreed.</blockquote> <p>谷歌的研究人员称他们仔细研究了加州的机动车条例，认定因为驾驶员可以纠正任何错误的发生，所以试验车是合法的。而陆先生也表示同意。</p> <blockquote>Scientists and engineers have been designing autonomous vehicles since the mid-1960s, but crucial innovation happened in 2004 when the Pentagon’s research arm began its Grand Challenge.</blockquote> <p>科学家和工程师们从 20 世纪 60 年代中叶就开始设计自动车辆了，但到了 2004 年五角大楼研究机构发起大挑战赛时才迎来了关键性的革新。</p> <blockquote>The first contest ended in failure, but in 2005, Dr. Thrun’s Stanford team built the car that won a race with a rival vehicle built by a team from Carnegie Mellon University. Less than two years later, another event proved that autonomous vehicles could drive safely in urban settings.</blockquote> <p>第一次大赛以失败告终，但到了 2005 年，特隆博士的斯坦福团队制造的汽车在和竞争对手卡内基梅隆大学的汽车的比赛中获胜。不到两年以后，另一次活动再次证明了自动车辆能够在城市道路设置中安全行驶。</p> <blockquote>Advances have been so encouraging that Dr. Thrun sounds like an evangelist when he speaks of robot cars. There is their potential to reduce fuel consumption by eliminating heavy-footed stop-and-go drivers and, given the reduced possibility of accidents, to ultimately build more lightweight vehicles.</blockquote> <p>研究进展如此令人振奋，以至于特隆博士在谈到自动汽车时语气好似布道。他们有潜力通过摒弃大力的刹车和加速来减少油耗，并减少事故的可能性，最终创造出更加轻量级的车辆。</p> <blockquote>There is even the farther-off prospect of cars that do not need anyone behind the wheel. That would allow the cars to be summoned electronically, so that people could share them. Fewer cars would then be needed, reducing the need for parking spaces, which consume valuable land.</blockquote> <p>他们甚至构想了更进一步的不需要驾驶员的车辆概念。这能够让汽车通过电子通信方式随叫随到，这样一来人们就可以共享车辆了。这样就不需要这么多的车辆，还能减少停车的空间占用，节约出宝贵的土地。</p> <blockquote>And, of course, the cars could save humans from themselves. “Can we text twice as much while driving, without the guilt?” Dr. Thrun said in a recent talk. “Yes, we can, if only cars will drive themselves.”</blockquote> <p>而且，这些车当然可以解放人力。“我们能毫无负罪感地在驾车时发更多的短信息吗？”特隆博士在最近的一次谈话中说，“没错，我们可以这么做，只要汽车能够自动行驶。”</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/105279/142401#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/166284/142361?from=rss_related\">谷歌竟也玩起了汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180478/142155?from=rss_related\">汽车声音的未来</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/153650/141988?from=rss_related\">为我们的学术研究创建Google自定义搜索</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180619/141919?from=rss_related\">道路上的谷歌无人驾驶汽车</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/180619/141910?from=rss_related\">谷歌成功测试无人驾驶汽车</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422733068/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/105279/142401\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733068/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733068/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>") (pubDate nil "Tue, 12 Oct 2010 13:16:24 +0800") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142401") (dc:creator nil "jays") (fs:srclink nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/105279/142401") (fs:srcfeed nil "http://www.yeeyan.org/feed/category/410") (fs:itemid nil "feedsky/yeeyan-tech/~8024233/422733068/5032246"))) ("短信, 推特，然后竞选成功？还没有那么快" "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/10/07/AR2010100707157.html?wpisrc=nl_tech\">Text, tweet, win? Not so fast</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/8312\">xiaoye</a></p><blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Text, tweet, win? Not so fast.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">短信, 推特，然后竞选成功？还没有那么快</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\"><br /> By Shailagh Murrayand John Wagner</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\"><span style=\"color:#666666;\">作者： Shailagh Murrayand John Wagner</span></p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Friday, October 8, 2010</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">周五，2010年10月8日</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Robert L. Ehrlich Jr. has lots of \"friends\" - 58,610 of them, to be exact.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Robert L. Ehrlich Jr. 有很多“朋友” - 确切点说，他有58,610 位朋友</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">That's the number of people who support the former Maryland governor on Facebook, and as he campaigns across the state trying to get his old job back, he mentions his online pals whenever he can. Ehrlich's Democratic opponent, Gov. Martin O'Malley, can claim a mere 24,516 Facebook supporters. \"That proves I'm friendlier,\" Ehrlich told the crowd at a corn roast Saturday in Baltimore County, and \"more popular.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">这是前马里兰州地方长官在Facebook上的朋友数目，当他在全州进行竞选活动，争夺他原有工作位置时，他在任何场合提到他的在线伙伴。Ehrlich的民主党对手，Gov. Martin O'Malley, 声称他有大约24,516名Facebook支持者。“这就证明我是更加亲善的” Ehrlich 在贝尔的摩的周六玉米烧烤会上告诉人们，“我更受到欢迎”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">No doubt, if the election were held on Facebook, Ehrlich would be the runaway winner. But in Maryland, where the election actually will be held, a Washington Post poll has him trailing O'Malley by 11 points.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">毫无疑问，如果在Facebook上进行选举，Ehrlich 会是胜出者。但是在马里兰州真正举行的选举中，华盛顿邮报报导他比O'Malley落后11个点。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Ehrlich is one of many politicians this year who have discovered the limits of online friendship.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Ehrlich 是今年发现在线朋友有限性的很多政治家之一。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">President Obama's 2008 campaign showed how the Internet could be used to organize grass-roots supporters into a nationwide political force. Now House, Senate and gubernatorial candidates across the country are finding it isn't so easy to duplicate Obama's results.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">奥巴马总统2008年选举显示出Internet 可以被用于组织草根民众从而形成全国范围的政治力量。现在House， Senate和其他全国的州长候选人发现复制奥巴马的成功经验并不是很容易。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">To show that they \"get\" the Web, too, politicians are venturing online to raise money, organize volunteers and communicate directly with supporters. They rack up Facebook friends, tweet their every thought and action (or assign some poor young staffer to do it for them), shell out for Obama-style iPhone applications and wait for the Web to work its magic.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">为了显示他们“争取”到了Web, 政治家们勇于在线筹募资金，组织志愿者以及和支持者直接进行沟通。他们争取Facebook上的朋友，Tweet他们的每一个思考和动作（或者委托一些贫穷的年轻雇员代替他们做），为奥巴马式的iphone应用付款，同时等待着Web发挥它的魔力。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">A lot of them have been disappointed to find that all that motion doesn't necessarily translate into votes.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">他们中的很多人已经很失望地发现这种美好意向并不总是转换为选票。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"So you have 50,000 Facebook fans - what the heck are you going to do with them?\" said Vincent Harris, a GOP new-media consultant for numerous 2010 candidates. \"Campaigns this cycle are in this frenzy of numbers, numbers, numbers. But how do you effectively reach these people and activate them?\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">\"你有50,000 Facebook 粉丝- 可是你要怎样利用他们呢？\" Vincent Harris说到， 为很多2010年候选人提供顾问服务的GOP 新媒体顾问。“这一轮的竞选者疯狂的增加粉丝数目。但是他们如何有效地影响到这些人并且激活他们呢？”&nbsp; <br /> </p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">When Harris signed on as the new-media adviser to Republican Robert F. McDonnell's campaign for Virginia governor last year, the candidate asked for all the Obama bells and whistles. Harris adopted a sophisticated text-messaging system that allowed the campaign to send quick news flashes to supporters.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">当Harris 去年成为弗吉尼亚州竞选地方长官-&nbsp;共和党人Robert F. McDonnell 的新媒体顾问时，这名候选人要求把奥巴马那些华而不实的东西都用上。Harris 采用了一套复杂的短消息系统把竞选活动的最新信息发送给支持者。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">McDonnell spent $150,000 to buy the very latest in texting technology. The campaign put its SMS \"short code\" on T-shirts, online ads and rally placards.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">McDonnell 花费了$150,000购买最新的短信息技术。竞选组织者把短消息的“短代码”印在T-shirt, 在线广告以及集会的招贴画上。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">But by Election Day, the campaign had collected only about 9,000 mobile numbers, compared with more than 250,000 plain old e-mail addresses. This year, Harris has discouraged his clients from investing in texting. \"I don't think mobile is there yet,\" Harris said.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">但是，截止选举日，竞选组织者总共只收集到了9,000个移动号码，而传统的电子邮件地址却超过了250,000个。今年，Harris 已经开始阻止他的客户投资短信息了。“我不认为移动方式有所帮助”Harris 说。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Apps for the iPhone are another popular campaign toy. But they can run in the thousands of dollars to create and aside from a certain hipster quality don't tend to reach many voters. And neither text messaging nor apps can be used for political fundraising, making them even less effective as campaign tools.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">iPhone Apps是另一种流行的竞选玩具。他们虽然花费几千美金制作出来，而且具有赶时髦的质量，却没有影响到很多的选举者。不论是短信息还是iPhone应用都不可以用于政治筹款，这使得他们作为选举工具来说效果更少。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Some candidates are clearly more agile than others in adopting new ways of doing things. McDonnell struggled to make use of the cell numbers he collected, but GOP candidate Scott Brown used text messages to deploy a guerrilla army in his winning campaign to succeed the late Massachusetts senator Edward M. Kennedy.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">有些候选人在采纳新方法做事情方面要更迅捷一些， McDonnell 对他收集的手机号码不是很顺畅地利用，而GOP 候选人Scott Brown 则利用短信息部署了一只选举阵营中的游击队，并且成功地战胜了马塞诸塞州参议员 Edward M. Kennedy。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Whenever Brown's Democratic opponent, Martha Coakley, appeared on a talk-radio show, the Brown campaign would text the cellphones of some 7,000 supporters, asking them to light up the phone lines with critical questions.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">当Brown 的民主党对手Martha Coakley 在一场广播对话节目中出现时， Brown的竞选班子给7000名支持者发了手机短信，让他们打进电话提出批评性质的问题。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Rob Willington, Brown's new-media strategist, was inspired by the text message Obama sent to supporters announcing Joseph R. Biden Jr. as his running mate. But Willington took the idea a step further, using the text message as a real-time call to action.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Rob&nbsp;Wellington, Brown的新媒体策略师受到奥巴马发送短信息给支持者宣布Joseph R. Biden Jr. 作为竞选伙伴的启发。但是，Willington把这个点子更推进了一部，用短信息作为实时行动的命令。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"What I love is, creativity can make up for the lack of bucks,\" Willington said. \"Because of the technology, if you have an interesting candidate with an interesting message, that can go viral and be worth hundreds of thousands of dollars. That was never possible. Real, raw talent has the ability to break through all the noise out there.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“我喜欢的是，创意可以弥补资金的短缺，” Willington说。“因为使用技术的缘故，如果你有位有趣的候选人又有有趣的信息，你可以把信息像病毒似的传播出去，这可以价值成百上千美元。那是非常有可能的。真实的天赋可以突破所有的噪音”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Similarly, the Democratic National Committee has created a new iPhone mapping app for campaign workers to use while canvassing neighborhoods on behalf of candidates. The app improves their chances of finding a receptive audience by pointing them to the homes of people who voted for Obama. It is widely viewed as one of the most innovative tools of the 2010 campaign.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">相似的情况， 民主党全国委员会创建了一个新的iPhone 匹配应用，提供给竞选班子在社区代表候选人进行拉票活动时使用。这个应用提高了他们找到乐于倾听的听众的机会，并且向他们指出已经投票给奥巴马的家庭。这个应用被广泛认为是最具有创新性的2010年选举工具。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">One of the most widely copied campaign innovations from 2008 isn't very techie at all: It's the home phone bank, which saves campaigns money on office rent and telephone bills by having volunteers make recruiting calls from their own houses. Tea party groups have been especially effective at using the technique, recruiting activists to make campaign calls on behalf of tea party candidates in districts thousands of miles away from where they live.</blockquote> <span style=\"line-height:25px;\">2008年以来一个最被广泛复制的竞选创新活动其实一点也不技术：就是家庭电话银行，通过让志愿者从他们自己家打电话进行招募，竞选班子可以节省用在租赁办公室的费用以及电话费用。茶话会组织很好的使用了这个方法，招募积极分子让他们在千里之外的他们自己家里代表茶话会组织进行选举电话会议。<br /> </span><blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">The one online tool that seems to have lost a lot of its appeal to voters is the candidate's Web site. Every office seeker has one, but they tend toward the dull and dutiful and inspire few repeat visitors.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">有一个在线工具对于选民不再有很多吸引力，那就是候选人的web站点。每个谋求官职的人都有一个，但是他们都很无趣，不再吸引访问者再次光顾。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"Nobody is going to a politician's Web site every day,\" said Wesley Donehue, a GOP consultant in South Carolina whose clients include Sen. Jim DeMint (R-S.C.) and whose sharply worded Twitter posts have helped him achieve celebrity among tea party activists. Some politicians might still be struggling to figure out how to use the new tools, Donehue said, but \"if the politician is where the people are, social networks are going to become the new hub of campaign activity.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“没有人会每天都到政治家的web站点去的” Wesley Donehue 说，南卡罗尼亚的GOP顾问，他的客户包括Sen. Jim DeMint(R-S.C.) 。 他很犀利的指出Twitter 发布的信息帮助他在茶话会积极分子中累积名声。也许有些政治家还在努力找到如何使用新工具的方法， Donehue 说， 但是“如果政治家是在人们当中，社交网络将会成为竞选活动的中心。”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">David All, a Capitol Hill veteran and GOP new-media strategist, agrees.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">David All, Capitol Hill的资深人员以及GOP新媒体策略师，非常同意。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"The whole model is about to shift on its head,\" said All, who organized his industry's first bipartisan conference last week in Washington. \"The only thing that is going to slow that down is the old guard, trying to hold on to the old-school ways.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“整个的模式是将要调转方向的”， All说， 他上周在华盛顿组织了业内首次两党合作会议。“只有一件事能让这个趋势慢下来，那些守旧者他们固守着旧的学院派方式。”</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/8312/141644#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/xiaowenjuan/109117?from=rss_related\">华尔街日报iPad版，看起来很美</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/62287/69085?from=rss_related\">研究表明：读者愿意为网络新闻付费</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/starshooter/55871?from=rss_related\">青少年媒体消费习惯——惊倒伦敦的摩根斯坦利实习生报告</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/69080/55408?from=rss_related\">青少年的媒体消费习惯：一份震惊业界的实习生报告</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/Annihilation/41705?from=rss_related\">新闻业的新生</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422733108/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/8312/141644\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733108/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733108/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>" "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/8312/141644" (19635 56978) old 5 nil nil ((title nil "短信, 推特，然后竞选成功？还没有那么快") (link nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/8312/141644") (created ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T04:05:38+00:00") (issued ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T04:05:38+00:00") (modified ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T04:05:38+00:00") (id ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/141644") (author ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) (name nil "xiaoye") (uri nil "http://space.yeeyan.org/u/8312")) (content ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom") (type . "html")) "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/10/07/AR2010100707157.html?wpisrc=nl_tech\">Text, tweet, win? Not so fast</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/8312\">xiaoye</a></p><blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Text, tweet, win? Not so fast.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">短信, 推特，然后竞选成功？还没有那么快</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\"><br /> By Shailagh Murrayand John Wagner</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\"><span style=\"color:#666666;\">作者： Shailagh Murrayand John Wagner</span></p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Friday, October 8, 2010</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">周五，2010年10月8日</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Robert L. Ehrlich Jr. has lots of \"friends\" - 58,610 of them, to be exact.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Robert L. Ehrlich Jr. 有很多“朋友” - 确切点说，他有58,610 位朋友</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">That's the number of people who support the former Maryland governor on Facebook, and as he campaigns across the state trying to get his old job back, he mentions his online pals whenever he can. Ehrlich's Democratic opponent, Gov. Martin O'Malley, can claim a mere 24,516 Facebook supporters. \"That proves I'm friendlier,\" Ehrlich told the crowd at a corn roast Saturday in Baltimore County, and \"more popular.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">这是前马里兰州地方长官在Facebook上的朋友数目，当他在全州进行竞选活动，争夺他原有工作位置时，他在任何场合提到他的在线伙伴。Ehrlich的民主党对手，Gov. Martin O'Malley, 声称他有大约24,516名Facebook支持者。“这就证明我是更加亲善的” Ehrlich 在贝尔的摩的周六玉米烧烤会上告诉人们，“我更受到欢迎”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">No doubt, if the election were held on Facebook, Ehrlich would be the runaway winner. But in Maryland, where the election actually will be held, a Washington Post poll has him trailing O'Malley by 11 points.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">毫无疑问，如果在Facebook上进行选举，Ehrlich 会是胜出者。但是在马里兰州真正举行的选举中，华盛顿邮报报导他比O'Malley落后11个点。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Ehrlich is one of many politicians this year who have discovered the limits of online friendship.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Ehrlich 是今年发现在线朋友有限性的很多政治家之一。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">President Obama's 2008 campaign showed how the Internet could be used to organize grass-roots supporters into a nationwide political force. Now House, Senate and gubernatorial candidates across the country are finding it isn't so easy to duplicate Obama's results.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">奥巴马总统2008年选举显示出Internet 可以被用于组织草根民众从而形成全国范围的政治力量。现在House， Senate和其他全国的州长候选人发现复制奥巴马的成功经验并不是很容易。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">To show that they \"get\" the Web, too, politicians are venturing online to raise money, organize volunteers and communicate directly with supporters. They rack up Facebook friends, tweet their every thought and action (or assign some poor young staffer to do it for them), shell out for Obama-style iPhone applications and wait for the Web to work its magic.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">为了显示他们“争取”到了Web, 政治家们勇于在线筹募资金，组织志愿者以及和支持者直接进行沟通。他们争取Facebook上的朋友，Tweet他们的每一个思考和动作（或者委托一些贫穷的年轻雇员代替他们做），为奥巴马式的iphone应用付款，同时等待着Web发挥它的魔力。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">A lot of them have been disappointed to find that all that motion doesn't necessarily translate into votes.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">他们中的很多人已经很失望地发现这种美好意向并不总是转换为选票。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"So you have 50,000 Facebook fans - what the heck are you going to do with them?\" said Vincent Harris, a GOP new-media consultant for numerous 2010 candidates. \"Campaigns this cycle are in this frenzy of numbers, numbers, numbers. But how do you effectively reach these people and activate them?\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">\"你有50,000 Facebook 粉丝- 可是你要怎样利用他们呢？\" Vincent Harris说到， 为很多2010年候选人提供顾问服务的GOP 新媒体顾问。“这一轮的竞选者疯狂的增加粉丝数目。但是他们如何有效地影响到这些人并且激活他们呢？”&nbsp; <br /> </p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">When Harris signed on as the new-media adviser to Republican Robert F. McDonnell's campaign for Virginia governor last year, the candidate asked for all the Obama bells and whistles. Harris adopted a sophisticated text-messaging system that allowed the campaign to send quick news flashes to supporters.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">当Harris 去年成为弗吉尼亚州竞选地方长官-&nbsp;共和党人Robert F. McDonnell 的新媒体顾问时，这名候选人要求把奥巴马那些华而不实的东西都用上。Harris 采用了一套复杂的短消息系统把竞选活动的最新信息发送给支持者。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">McDonnell spent $150,000 to buy the very latest in texting technology. The campaign put its SMS \"short code\" on T-shirts, online ads and rally placards.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">McDonnell 花费了$150,000购买最新的短信息技术。竞选组织者把短消息的“短代码”印在T-shirt, 在线广告以及集会的招贴画上。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">But by Election Day, the campaign had collected only about 9,000 mobile numbers, compared with more than 250,000 plain old e-mail addresses. This year, Harris has discouraged his clients from investing in texting. \"I don't think mobile is there yet,\" Harris said.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">但是，截止选举日，竞选组织者总共只收集到了9,000个移动号码，而传统的电子邮件地址却超过了250,000个。今年，Harris 已经开始阻止他的客户投资短信息了。“我不认为移动方式有所帮助”Harris 说。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Apps for the iPhone are another popular campaign toy. But they can run in the thousands of dollars to create and aside from a certain hipster quality don't tend to reach many voters. And neither text messaging nor apps can be used for political fundraising, making them even less effective as campaign tools.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">iPhone Apps是另一种流行的竞选玩具。他们虽然花费几千美金制作出来，而且具有赶时髦的质量，却没有影响到很多的选举者。不论是短信息还是iPhone应用都不可以用于政治筹款，这使得他们作为选举工具来说效果更少。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Some candidates are clearly more agile than others in adopting new ways of doing things. McDonnell struggled to make use of the cell numbers he collected, but GOP candidate Scott Brown used text messages to deploy a guerrilla army in his winning campaign to succeed the late Massachusetts senator Edward M. Kennedy.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">有些候选人在采纳新方法做事情方面要更迅捷一些， McDonnell 对他收集的手机号码不是很顺畅地利用，而GOP 候选人Scott Brown 则利用短信息部署了一只选举阵营中的游击队，并且成功地战胜了马塞诸塞州参议员 Edward M. Kennedy。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Whenever Brown's Democratic opponent, Martha Coakley, appeared on a talk-radio show, the Brown campaign would text the cellphones of some 7,000 supporters, asking them to light up the phone lines with critical questions.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">当Brown 的民主党对手Martha Coakley 在一场广播对话节目中出现时， Brown的竞选班子给7000名支持者发了手机短信，让他们打进电话提出批评性质的问题。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Rob Willington, Brown's new-media strategist, was inspired by the text message Obama sent to supporters announcing Joseph R. Biden Jr. as his running mate. But Willington took the idea a step further, using the text message as a real-time call to action.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Rob&nbsp;Wellington, Brown的新媒体策略师受到奥巴马发送短信息给支持者宣布Joseph R. Biden Jr. 作为竞选伙伴的启发。但是，Willington把这个点子更推进了一部，用短信息作为实时行动的命令。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"What I love is, creativity can make up for the lack of bucks,\" Willington said. \"Because of the technology, if you have an interesting candidate with an interesting message, that can go viral and be worth hundreds of thousands of dollars. That was never possible. Real, raw talent has the ability to break through all the noise out there.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“我喜欢的是，创意可以弥补资金的短缺，” Willington说。“因为使用技术的缘故，如果你有位有趣的候选人又有有趣的信息，你可以把信息像病毒似的传播出去，这可以价值成百上千美元。那是非常有可能的。真实的天赋可以突破所有的噪音”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Similarly, the Democratic National Committee has created a new iPhone mapping app for campaign workers to use while canvassing neighborhoods on behalf of candidates. The app improves their chances of finding a receptive audience by pointing them to the homes of people who voted for Obama. It is widely viewed as one of the most innovative tools of the 2010 campaign.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">相似的情况， 民主党全国委员会创建了一个新的iPhone 匹配应用，提供给竞选班子在社区代表候选人进行拉票活动时使用。这个应用提高了他们找到乐于倾听的听众的机会，并且向他们指出已经投票给奥巴马的家庭。这个应用被广泛认为是最具有创新性的2010年选举工具。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">One of the most widely copied campaign innovations from 2008 isn't very techie at all: It's the home phone bank, which saves campaigns money on office rent and telephone bills by having volunteers make recruiting calls from their own houses. Tea party groups have been especially effective at using the technique, recruiting activists to make campaign calls on behalf of tea party candidates in districts thousands of miles away from where they live.</blockquote> <span style=\"line-height:25px;\">2008年以来一个最被广泛复制的竞选创新活动其实一点也不技术：就是家庭电话银行，通过让志愿者从他们自己家打电话进行招募，竞选班子可以节省用在租赁办公室的费用以及电话费用。茶话会组织很好的使用了这个方法，招募积极分子让他们在千里之外的他们自己家里代表茶话会组织进行选举电话会议。<br /> </span><blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">The one online tool that seems to have lost a lot of its appeal to voters is the candidate's Web site. Every office seeker has one, but they tend toward the dull and dutiful and inspire few repeat visitors.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">有一个在线工具对于选民不再有很多吸引力，那就是候选人的web站点。每个谋求官职的人都有一个，但是他们都很无趣，不再吸引访问者再次光顾。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"Nobody is going to a politician's Web site every day,\" said Wesley Donehue, a GOP consultant in South Carolina whose clients include Sen. Jim DeMint (R-S.C.) and whose sharply worded Twitter posts have helped him achieve celebrity among tea party activists. Some politicians might still be struggling to figure out how to use the new tools, Donehue said, but \"if the politician is where the people are, social networks are going to become the new hub of campaign activity.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“没有人会每天都到政治家的web站点去的” Wesley Donehue 说，南卡罗尼亚的GOP顾问，他的客户包括Sen. Jim DeMint(R-S.C.) 。 他很犀利的指出Twitter 发布的信息帮助他在茶话会积极分子中累积名声。也许有些政治家还在努力找到如何使用新工具的方法， Donehue 说， 但是“如果政治家是在人们当中，社交网络将会成为竞选活动的中心。”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">David All, a Capitol Hill veteran and GOP new-media strategist, agrees.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">David All, Capitol Hill的资深人员以及GOP新媒体策略师，非常同意。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"The whole model is about to shift on its head,\" said All, who organized his industry's first bipartisan conference last week in Washington. \"The only thing that is going to slow that down is the old guard, trying to hold on to the old-school ways.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“整个的模式是将要调转方向的”， All说， 他上周在华盛顿组织了业内首次两党合作会议。“只有一件事能让这个趋势慢下来，那些守旧者他们固守着旧的学院派方式。”</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/8312/141644#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/xiaowenjuan/109117?from=rss_related\">华尔街日报iPad版，看起来很美</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/62287/69085?from=rss_related\">研究表明：读者愿意为网络新闻付费</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/starshooter/55871?from=rss_related\">青少年媒体消费习惯——惊倒伦敦的摩根斯坦利实习生报告</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/69080/55408?from=rss_related\">青少年的媒体消费习惯：一份震惊业界的实习生报告</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/Annihilation/41705?from=rss_related\">新闻业的新生</a></p>") (content:encoded nil "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/10/07/AR2010100707157.html?wpisrc=nl_tech\">Text, tweet, win? Not so fast</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/8312\">xiaoye</a></p><blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Text, tweet, win? Not so fast.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">短信, 推特，然后竞选成功？还没有那么快</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\"><br /> By Shailagh Murrayand John Wagner</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\"><span style=\"color:#666666;\">作者： Shailagh Murrayand John Wagner</span></p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Friday, October 8, 2010</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">周五，2010年10月8日</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Robert L. Ehrlich Jr. has lots of \"friends\" - 58,610 of them, to be exact.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Robert L. Ehrlich Jr. 有很多“朋友” - 确切点说，他有58,610 位朋友</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">That's the number of people who support the former Maryland governor on Facebook, and as he campaigns across the state trying to get his old job back, he mentions his online pals whenever he can. Ehrlich's Democratic opponent, Gov. Martin O'Malley, can claim a mere 24,516 Facebook supporters. \"That proves I'm friendlier,\" Ehrlich told the crowd at a corn roast Saturday in Baltimore County, and \"more popular.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">这是前马里兰州地方长官在Facebook上的朋友数目，当他在全州进行竞选活动，争夺他原有工作位置时，他在任何场合提到他的在线伙伴。Ehrlich的民主党对手，Gov. Martin O'Malley, 声称他有大约24,516名Facebook支持者。“这就证明我是更加亲善的” Ehrlich 在贝尔的摩的周六玉米烧烤会上告诉人们，“我更受到欢迎”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">No doubt, if the election were held on Facebook, Ehrlich would be the runaway winner. But in Maryland, where the election actually will be held, a Washington Post poll has him trailing O'Malley by 11 points.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">毫无疑问，如果在Facebook上进行选举，Ehrlich 会是胜出者。但是在马里兰州真正举行的选举中，华盛顿邮报报导他比O'Malley落后11个点。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Ehrlich is one of many politicians this year who have discovered the limits of online friendship.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Ehrlich 是今年发现在线朋友有限性的很多政治家之一。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">President Obama's 2008 campaign showed how the Internet could be used to organize grass-roots supporters into a nationwide political force. Now House, Senate and gubernatorial candidates across the country are finding it isn't so easy to duplicate Obama's results.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">奥巴马总统2008年选举显示出Internet 可以被用于组织草根民众从而形成全国范围的政治力量。现在House， Senate和其他全国的州长候选人发现复制奥巴马的成功经验并不是很容易。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">To show that they \"get\" the Web, too, politicians are venturing online to raise money, organize volunteers and communicate directly with supporters. They rack up Facebook friends, tweet their every thought and action (or assign some poor young staffer to do it for them), shell out for Obama-style iPhone applications and wait for the Web to work its magic.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">为了显示他们“争取”到了Web, 政治家们勇于在线筹募资金，组织志愿者以及和支持者直接进行沟通。他们争取Facebook上的朋友，Tweet他们的每一个思考和动作（或者委托一些贫穷的年轻雇员代替他们做），为奥巴马式的iphone应用付款，同时等待着Web发挥它的魔力。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">A lot of them have been disappointed to find that all that motion doesn't necessarily translate into votes.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">他们中的很多人已经很失望地发现这种美好意向并不总是转换为选票。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"So you have 50,000 Facebook fans - what the heck are you going to do with them?\" said Vincent Harris, a GOP new-media consultant for numerous 2010 candidates. \"Campaigns this cycle are in this frenzy of numbers, numbers, numbers. But how do you effectively reach these people and activate them?\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">\"你有50,000 Facebook 粉丝- 可是你要怎样利用他们呢？\" Vincent Harris说到， 为很多2010年候选人提供顾问服务的GOP 新媒体顾问。“这一轮的竞选者疯狂的增加粉丝数目。但是他们如何有效地影响到这些人并且激活他们呢？”&nbsp; <br /> </p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">When Harris signed on as the new-media adviser to Republican Robert F. McDonnell's campaign for Virginia governor last year, the candidate asked for all the Obama bells and whistles. Harris adopted a sophisticated text-messaging system that allowed the campaign to send quick news flashes to supporters.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">当Harris 去年成为弗吉尼亚州竞选地方长官-&nbsp;共和党人Robert F. McDonnell 的新媒体顾问时，这名候选人要求把奥巴马那些华而不实的东西都用上。Harris 采用了一套复杂的短消息系统把竞选活动的最新信息发送给支持者。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">McDonnell spent $150,000 to buy the very latest in texting technology. The campaign put its SMS \"short code\" on T-shirts, online ads and rally placards.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">McDonnell 花费了$150,000购买最新的短信息技术。竞选组织者把短消息的“短代码”印在T-shirt, 在线广告以及集会的招贴画上。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">But by Election Day, the campaign had collected only about 9,000 mobile numbers, compared with more than 250,000 plain old e-mail addresses. This year, Harris has discouraged his clients from investing in texting. \"I don't think mobile is there yet,\" Harris said.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">但是，截止选举日，竞选组织者总共只收集到了9,000个移动号码，而传统的电子邮件地址却超过了250,000个。今年，Harris 已经开始阻止他的客户投资短信息了。“我不认为移动方式有所帮助”Harris 说。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Apps for the iPhone are another popular campaign toy. But they can run in the thousands of dollars to create and aside from a certain hipster quality don't tend to reach many voters. And neither text messaging nor apps can be used for political fundraising, making them even less effective as campaign tools.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">iPhone Apps是另一种流行的竞选玩具。他们虽然花费几千美金制作出来，而且具有赶时髦的质量，却没有影响到很多的选举者。不论是短信息还是iPhone应用都不可以用于政治筹款，这使得他们作为选举工具来说效果更少。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Some candidates are clearly more agile than others in adopting new ways of doing things. McDonnell struggled to make use of the cell numbers he collected, but GOP candidate Scott Brown used text messages to deploy a guerrilla army in his winning campaign to succeed the late Massachusetts senator Edward M. Kennedy.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">有些候选人在采纳新方法做事情方面要更迅捷一些， McDonnell 对他收集的手机号码不是很顺畅地利用，而GOP 候选人Scott Brown 则利用短信息部署了一只选举阵营中的游击队，并且成功地战胜了马塞诸塞州参议员 Edward M. Kennedy。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Whenever Brown's Democratic opponent, Martha Coakley, appeared on a talk-radio show, the Brown campaign would text the cellphones of some 7,000 supporters, asking them to light up the phone lines with critical questions.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">当Brown 的民主党对手Martha Coakley 在一场广播对话节目中出现时， Brown的竞选班子给7000名支持者发了手机短信，让他们打进电话提出批评性质的问题。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Rob Willington, Brown's new-media strategist, was inspired by the text message Obama sent to supporters announcing Joseph R. Biden Jr. as his running mate. But Willington took the idea a step further, using the text message as a real-time call to action.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">Rob&nbsp;Wellington, Brown的新媒体策略师受到奥巴马发送短信息给支持者宣布Joseph R. Biden Jr. 作为竞选伙伴的启发。但是，Willington把这个点子更推进了一部，用短信息作为实时行动的命令。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"What I love is, creativity can make up for the lack of bucks,\" Willington said. \"Because of the technology, if you have an interesting candidate with an interesting message, that can go viral and be worth hundreds of thousands of dollars. That was never possible. Real, raw talent has the ability to break through all the noise out there.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“我喜欢的是，创意可以弥补资金的短缺，” Willington说。“因为使用技术的缘故，如果你有位有趣的候选人又有有趣的信息，你可以把信息像病毒似的传播出去，这可以价值成百上千美元。那是非常有可能的。真实的天赋可以突破所有的噪音”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">Similarly, the Democratic National Committee has created a new iPhone mapping app for campaign workers to use while canvassing neighborhoods on behalf of candidates. The app improves their chances of finding a receptive audience by pointing them to the homes of people who voted for Obama. It is widely viewed as one of the most innovative tools of the 2010 campaign.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">相似的情况， 民主党全国委员会创建了一个新的iPhone 匹配应用，提供给竞选班子在社区代表候选人进行拉票活动时使用。这个应用提高了他们找到乐于倾听的听众的机会，并且向他们指出已经投票给奥巴马的家庭。这个应用被广泛认为是最具有创新性的2010年选举工具。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">One of the most widely copied campaign innovations from 2008 isn't very techie at all: It's the home phone bank, which saves campaigns money on office rent and telephone bills by having volunteers make recruiting calls from their own houses. Tea party groups have been especially effective at using the technique, recruiting activists to make campaign calls on behalf of tea party candidates in districts thousands of miles away from where they live.</blockquote> <span style=\"line-height:25px;\">2008年以来一个最被广泛复制的竞选创新活动其实一点也不技术：就是家庭电话银行，通过让志愿者从他们自己家打电话进行招募，竞选班子可以节省用在租赁办公室的费用以及电话费用。茶话会组织很好的使用了这个方法，招募积极分子让他们在千里之外的他们自己家里代表茶话会组织进行选举电话会议。<br /> </span><blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">The one online tool that seems to have lost a lot of its appeal to voters is the candidate's Web site. Every office seeker has one, but they tend toward the dull and dutiful and inspire few repeat visitors.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">有一个在线工具对于选民不再有很多吸引力，那就是候选人的web站点。每个谋求官职的人都有一个，但是他们都很无趣，不再吸引访问者再次光顾。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"Nobody is going to a politician's Web site every day,\" said Wesley Donehue, a GOP consultant in South Carolina whose clients include Sen. Jim DeMint (R-S.C.) and whose sharply worded Twitter posts have helped him achieve celebrity among tea party activists. Some politicians might still be struggling to figure out how to use the new tools, Donehue said, but \"if the politician is where the people are, social networks are going to become the new hub of campaign activity.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“没有人会每天都到政治家的web站点去的” Wesley Donehue 说，南卡罗尼亚的GOP顾问，他的客户包括Sen. Jim DeMint(R-S.C.) 。 他很犀利的指出Twitter 发布的信息帮助他在茶话会积极分子中累积名声。也许有些政治家还在努力找到如何使用新工具的方法， Donehue 说， 但是“如果政治家是在人们当中，社交网络将会成为竞选活动的中心。”</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">David All, a Capitol Hill veteran and GOP new-media strategist, agrees.</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">David All, Capitol Hill的资深人员以及GOP新媒体策略师，非常同意。</p> <blockquote style=\"margin:14px 0px;background-color:#f6f6f6;padding:10px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;color:#666666;\">\"The whole model is about to shift on its head,\" said All, who organized his industry's first bipartisan conference last week in Washington. \"The only thing that is going to slow that down is the old guard, trying to hold on to the old-school ways.\"</blockquote> <p style=\"margin:14px 0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;\">“整个的模式是将要调转方向的”， All说， 他上周在华盛顿组织了业内首次两党合作会议。“只有一件事能让这个趋势慢下来，那些守旧者他们固守着旧的学院派方式。”</p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/8312/141644#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/xiaowenjuan/109117?from=rss_related\">华尔街日报iPad版，看起来很美</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/62287/69085?from=rss_related\">研究表明：读者愿意为网络新闻付费</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/starshooter/55871?from=rss_related\">青少年媒体消费习惯——惊倒伦敦的摩根斯坦利实习生报告</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/69080/55408?from=rss_related\">青少年的媒体消费习惯：一份震惊业界的实习生报告</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/Annihilation/41705?from=rss_related\">新闻业的新生</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422733108/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/8312/141644\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733108/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733108/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>") (pubDate nil "Tue, 12 Oct 2010 12:05:38 +0800") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/141644") (dc:creator nil "xiaoye") (fs:srclink nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/8312/141644") (fs:srcfeed nil "http://www.yeeyan.org/feed/category/410") (fs:itemid nil "feedsky/yeeyan-tech/~8024233/422733108/5032246"))) ("云语音的教训：案例研究" "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/start/2010/10/lessons-in-cloud-telephony-a-startup-case-study.php\">Lessons in Cloud Telephony: A Startup Case Study</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/博贤\">boxi</a></p><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:21px;font-size:14px;\"><div class=\"asset-body\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;clear:both;font:normal normal normal 14px/0.9em arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:1.5em;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><img src=\"http://rww.readwriteweb.netdna-cdn.com/whitedialphone.png\" align=\"left\" alt=\"\" border=\"0\" /><br /> </p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">尽管有关云的成本效益分析以及经济理论的文字已经铺天盖地，但其建设团队却甚少提及。本博文要讲正是这样的一只团队，以及其中一位老手的经验之谈。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">当讨论云电话的时候，有很多理由需要关注于人的因素。这不仅在于我们是在跟一种传统的媒介打交道（想想看：电话已经出现了100多年了），还在于它是一个高度管制的东西，这意味着任何云语音供应商实际上都是一家集成公司。</p> </div> <div id=\"more\" class=\"asset-more\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;clear:both;font:normal normal normal 14px/0.9em arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:1.5em;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">客座作者芬纳卡兰（TJ Thinakaran）是CallFire'的COO。CallFire是一家云语音的初创企业，最近在</p> <em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\">INC500的5000家成长最快的公司排行榜中位列</p> </em></em><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\"><a href=\"http://www.inc.com/inc5000/profile/callfire\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">285</a>，在通信业中排在第15位。本文是其个人</p> </em></span></span><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\"><a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/start/2010/10/www.onetj.com\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">博客</a></p> </em></em></em></em></span><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\">观点的删节版。</p> </em></em></span></em> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;\">云电话解决方案是在若干电话公司和用户之间搭建的管道，屏蔽了语音的复杂性，给人以简单的错觉。如果你认为这种无缝的集成是件简单的工作，把你的电话号码拨接到谷歌语音试试。结果很有可能是，除非你是<a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2009/08/09/how-i-learned-to-quit-the-iphone-and-love-google-voice/\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">迈克尔·阿灵顿（Michael Arrington）</a>，否则有你好过的。</span></p> </em> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">云的理念</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">由于云电话是一种集成的方式，创建此类解决方案的团队不得不既要有非常广泛的技能，同时还要有非常专业的理念。因此尽管对Linux内核调优、按需部署解决方案、发布复杂功能以及跟踪经过我们系统的上百万个电话中的任何一个等这些都是关键技能，更为重要的是团队横向思考的倾向以及边界规避的能力。简而言之，这是一种涉猎到许多不同的主题和领域，并将它们整合为一个针对所有不明确问题的非线性的解决方案。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<div class=\"pullquote\" style=\"margin-top:10px;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:10px;margin-left:10px;padding-top:10px;padding-right:10px;padding-bottom:10px;padding-left:10px;float:right;width:275px;font-size:1.2em;background-color:#ffe7e7;font-family:georgia, serif;font-style:italic;line-height:1.45em;\">傲慢反之，则是弃教养于不顾的信心。是愚蠢的自信。是无惧自己知识深浅、财力强弱而直面问题并解决问题的信念。</div> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">无论如何，这些技能组合以及思维方式都是难以成为独一无二的。实际上，在一项经常被引用的MIT经典<a href=\"http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=6100\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">研究</a>里，据证实，高效能的工程师最有可能是那些能与专业外的专家协商的人。 他们意识到自己问题领域的复杂性，并知道要利用多学科框架来解决上述问题的需求。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">这在跟以对变化谨慎著称的电信运营商打交道时尤为重要。作为一名前IBM人，我有幸跟许多符合模式的高效能的人士一起工作；然而，当我离开蓝色巨人（译注：指IBM）到CallFire时，我知道了云电话初创企业需要一种略为不同的性格类型。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训1：无知</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">说起来有点令人震惊，但CallFire一开始并没有构思出一个特别的商业计划或者特性。尽管我们拥有丰富的技术经验，但对于电信却是知之甚少。CallFire乃应客户之需而诞生的，其关注点在于交付跟客户有关的功能特性。一些行动都来自于这一个关注点。这是非常短期、非常快节奏的，几乎没有时间来考虑远期愿景和使命宣言。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">学会接受“不知道”这种感觉是困难的，尤其是由于你的一切成年生活都被刻意营造为专家时。你获得了自己的首份工作，通过展示自己所知道而非不知道的东西来塑造个人的职业生涯。不过，企业家精神在于不断去发现自己的无知。让你不断前行的，是对解决问题的关注，以及对自己产品的激情。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">所以，尽管我们也许并没有一个商业计划，但我们对业务的关注永不缺乏。许多的解决方案和手段并不漂亮，但正如牧牛竞技的信条所言，有时候你得“忘掉那该死的规矩，制住那头牛就行”。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训2：傲慢</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我学到的另一种性格方面的教训是，你要表现出一定程度的傲慢，好让别人知道你是认真的。信心转变成傲慢有一条清晰的接线，而初创企业经常会触碰那条线。信心是一种基本的信仰，你了解需要完成的东西是什么，因为你有合适的工具、受过良好的培训，可以那样做。傲慢反之，则是弃教养于不顾的信心。是愚蠢的自信。是无惧自己知识深浅、财力强弱而直面问题并解决之的信念。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">傲慢也是对规模的一种很好的心里代偿方式。在IBM的时候，你必须谦虚，因为你资源庞大、弹药充足，被视为一头800磅重的大猩猩，这意味着一丝傲慢表现都将令客户疏远。然而作为初创企业，你没有这种品牌认知度，因此坐在你对面的那个人很容易就会把你的谦卑误以为是缺乏能力。这会传染且是致命的，必须不惜一切代价加以避免。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">记住，我不是在为傲慢开一张空头支票。从错误中学习的意愿，以及倾听客户需求需要高度的谦逊，这对于公司的生存来说同样至关重要。然而，当你还在起步阶段时，你要应对那么多的<a href=\"http://www.ted.com/talks/richard_st_john_s_8_secrets_of_success.html\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">批评、拒绝、小人还有压力（C.R.A.P）</a>，光有信心并不能成事。你得脸皮够厚，把这一切抛诸脑后，然后不断开拓进取。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训3：激情</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我有幸跟工作努力、充满激情的一群人共事。但我要说这一点：在初创企业，激情并非可选部分。而是生存的必要条件。在IBM，我可能一样夜以继日、牺牲周末的时间，但在内心深处我知道，如果有个周末我不干活，或者某天5点钟就回家，股票并不会就此下挫。反之，在CallFire工作就不一样了，需要不断的努力工作，没有激情的根本无法难以为继。初创在工作日运作，却是在周末建设好的。每个周末不花时间去建设，下一周就会以失去机会表现出来。这种持之以恒的努力要是没有激情，绝对难以为继。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">激情给人以希望，让工作自己成为回报，并提供了需要的专注。在建设一家公司时尤其如此，因为有那么多事情需要你自己亲力亲为去打造，光靠努力工作是没有机会的。工作再刻苦，如果没有激情，公司都将没有冷效率。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">软件是苦差</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">事实上，编写出优质的软件已经成为，且永远都是一件艰苦的工作。云语音的秘诀是，如果有的话，创造出被&nbsp;<span id=\"apture_prvw1\" class=\"aptureLink \" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:0px !important;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;border-top-left-radius:4px 4px;border-top-right-radius:4px 4px;border-bottom-right-radius:4px 4px;border-bottom-left-radius:4px 4px;cursor:pointer !important;\"><span class=\"aptureLinkIcon\" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:11px !important;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;background-image:url(http://cdn.apture.com/media/imgs/link_icons.gif?v12) !important;background-position:100% -1348px;background-repeat:no-repeat no-repeat !important;\">&nbsp;</span><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grady%20Booch\" class=\"aptureLink snap_noshots\" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:0px !important;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;\">格雷迪·布奇（Grady Booch）</a></span>称为简单之幻象的东西。说是假象是因为优质的软件其建设基本上都是复杂的，但抽象化这种复杂性正是像CallFire这样的初创企业所面临的挑战。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我们总喜欢认定自己很<a href=\"http://www.ics.uci.edu/callfire\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">特别</a>，但却很难做到独一无二。有许多聪明人都在致力于解决某些真正的云语音问题。尽管如此，无论你在招人还是找工作，好好看看这个团队，因为任何人都将告诉你这一点：即便身处地狱，好的团队也能把你拉回战壕。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><small style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><a href=\"http://www.sxc.hu/photo/485645\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">vierdrie</a>供图</small></em></p> </div> </span><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/博贤/142008#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/160822/142159?from=rss_related\">童女经验</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/158447/141940?from=rss_related\">女孩悄悄话：女孩的语言能力更强吗？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/41906/141957?from=rss_related\">女性的语言能力真的更好吗？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/161833/141067?from=rss_related\">欧元区经济危机的历史教训【外交事务（一家之言）】</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/59868/105676?from=rss_related\">青少年自杀：网络的侵害（推荐）</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422677564/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/博贤/142008\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422677564/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422677564/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>" "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/博贤/142008" (19635 53648) old 6 nil nil ((title nil "云语音的教训：案例研究") (link nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/博贤/142008") (created ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T03:10:08+00:00") (issued ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T03:10:08+00:00") (modified ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T03:10:08+00:00") (id ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142008") (author ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) (name nil "boxi") (uri nil "http://space.yeeyan.org/u/博贤")) (content ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom") (type . "html")) "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/start/2010/10/lessons-in-cloud-telephony-a-startup-case-study.php\">Lessons in Cloud Telephony: A Startup Case Study</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/博贤\">boxi</a></p><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:21px;font-size:14px;\"><div class=\"asset-body\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;clear:both;font:normal normal normal 14px/0.9em arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:1.5em;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><img src=\"http://rww.readwriteweb.netdna-cdn.com/whitedialphone.png\" align=\"left\" alt=\"\" border=\"0\" /><br /> </p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">尽管有关云的成本效益分析以及经济理论的文字已经铺天盖地，但其建设团队却甚少提及。本博文要讲正是这样的一只团队，以及其中一位老手的经验之谈。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">当讨论云电话的时候，有很多理由需要关注于人的因素。这不仅在于我们是在跟一种传统的媒介打交道（想想看：电话已经出现了100多年了），还在于它是一个高度管制的东西，这意味着任何云语音供应商实际上都是一家集成公司。</p> </div> <div id=\"more\" class=\"asset-more\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;clear:both;font:normal normal normal 14px/0.9em arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:1.5em;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">客座作者芬纳卡兰（TJ Thinakaran）是CallFire'的COO。CallFire是一家云语音的初创企业，最近在</p> <em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\">INC500的5000家成长最快的公司排行榜中位列</p> </em></em><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\"><a href=\"http://www.inc.com/inc5000/profile/callfire\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">285</a>，在通信业中排在第15位。本文是其个人</p> </em></span></span><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\"><a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/start/2010/10/www.onetj.com\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">博客</a></p> </em></em></em></em></span><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\">观点的删节版。</p> </em></em></span></em> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;\">云电话解决方案是在若干电话公司和用户之间搭建的管道，屏蔽了语音的复杂性，给人以简单的错觉。如果你认为这种无缝的集成是件简单的工作，把你的电话号码拨接到谷歌语音试试。结果很有可能是，除非你是<a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2009/08/09/how-i-learned-to-quit-the-iphone-and-love-google-voice/\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">迈克尔·阿灵顿（Michael Arrington）</a>，否则有你好过的。</span></p> </em> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">云的理念</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">由于云电话是一种集成的方式，创建此类解决方案的团队不得不既要有非常广泛的技能，同时还要有非常专业的理念。因此尽管对Linux内核调优、按需部署解决方案、发布复杂功能以及跟踪经过我们系统的上百万个电话中的任何一个等这些都是关键技能，更为重要的是团队横向思考的倾向以及边界规避的能力。简而言之，这是一种涉猎到许多不同的主题和领域，并将它们整合为一个针对所有不明确问题的非线性的解决方案。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<div class=\"pullquote\" style=\"margin-top:10px;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:10px;margin-left:10px;padding-top:10px;padding-right:10px;padding-bottom:10px;padding-left:10px;float:right;width:275px;font-size:1.2em;background-color:#ffe7e7;font-family:georgia, serif;font-style:italic;line-height:1.45em;\">傲慢反之，则是弃教养于不顾的信心。是愚蠢的自信。是无惧自己知识深浅、财力强弱而直面问题并解决问题的信念。</div> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">无论如何，这些技能组合以及思维方式都是难以成为独一无二的。实际上，在一项经常被引用的MIT经典<a href=\"http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=6100\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">研究</a>里，据证实，高效能的工程师最有可能是那些能与专业外的专家协商的人。 他们意识到自己问题领域的复杂性，并知道要利用多学科框架来解决上述问题的需求。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">这在跟以对变化谨慎著称的电信运营商打交道时尤为重要。作为一名前IBM人，我有幸跟许多符合模式的高效能的人士一起工作；然而，当我离开蓝色巨人（译注：指IBM）到CallFire时，我知道了云电话初创企业需要一种略为不同的性格类型。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训1：无知</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">说起来有点令人震惊，但CallFire一开始并没有构思出一个特别的商业计划或者特性。尽管我们拥有丰富的技术经验，但对于电信却是知之甚少。CallFire乃应客户之需而诞生的，其关注点在于交付跟客户有关的功能特性。一些行动都来自于这一个关注点。这是非常短期、非常快节奏的，几乎没有时间来考虑远期愿景和使命宣言。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">学会接受“不知道”这种感觉是困难的，尤其是由于你的一切成年生活都被刻意营造为专家时。你获得了自己的首份工作，通过展示自己所知道而非不知道的东西来塑造个人的职业生涯。不过，企业家精神在于不断去发现自己的无知。让你不断前行的，是对解决问题的关注，以及对自己产品的激情。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">所以，尽管我们也许并没有一个商业计划，但我们对业务的关注永不缺乏。许多的解决方案和手段并不漂亮，但正如牧牛竞技的信条所言，有时候你得“忘掉那该死的规矩，制住那头牛就行”。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训2：傲慢</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我学到的另一种性格方面的教训是，你要表现出一定程度的傲慢，好让别人知道你是认真的。信心转变成傲慢有一条清晰的接线，而初创企业经常会触碰那条线。信心是一种基本的信仰，你了解需要完成的东西是什么，因为你有合适的工具、受过良好的培训，可以那样做。傲慢反之，则是弃教养于不顾的信心。是愚蠢的自信。是无惧自己知识深浅、财力强弱而直面问题并解决之的信念。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">傲慢也是对规模的一种很好的心里代偿方式。在IBM的时候，你必须谦虚，因为你资源庞大、弹药充足，被视为一头800磅重的大猩猩，这意味着一丝傲慢表现都将令客户疏远。然而作为初创企业，你没有这种品牌认知度，因此坐在你对面的那个人很容易就会把你的谦卑误以为是缺乏能力。这会传染且是致命的，必须不惜一切代价加以避免。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">记住，我不是在为傲慢开一张空头支票。从错误中学习的意愿，以及倾听客户需求需要高度的谦逊，这对于公司的生存来说同样至关重要。然而，当你还在起步阶段时，你要应对那么多的<a href=\"http://www.ted.com/talks/richard_st_john_s_8_secrets_of_success.html\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">批评、拒绝、小人还有压力（C.R.A.P）</a>，光有信心并不能成事。你得脸皮够厚，把这一切抛诸脑后，然后不断开拓进取。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训3：激情</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我有幸跟工作努力、充满激情的一群人共事。但我要说这一点：在初创企业，激情并非可选部分。而是生存的必要条件。在IBM，我可能一样夜以继日、牺牲周末的时间，但在内心深处我知道，如果有个周末我不干活，或者某天5点钟就回家，股票并不会就此下挫。反之，在CallFire工作就不一样了，需要不断的努力工作，没有激情的根本无法难以为继。初创在工作日运作，却是在周末建设好的。每个周末不花时间去建设，下一周就会以失去机会表现出来。这种持之以恒的努力要是没有激情，绝对难以为继。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">激情给人以希望，让工作自己成为回报，并提供了需要的专注。在建设一家公司时尤其如此，因为有那么多事情需要你自己亲力亲为去打造，光靠努力工作是没有机会的。工作再刻苦，如果没有激情，公司都将没有冷效率。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">软件是苦差</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">事实上，编写出优质的软件已经成为，且永远都是一件艰苦的工作。云语音的秘诀是，如果有的话，创造出被&nbsp;<span id=\"apture_prvw1\" class=\"aptureLink \" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:0px !important;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;border-top-left-radius:4px 4px;border-top-right-radius:4px 4px;border-bottom-right-radius:4px 4px;border-bottom-left-radius:4px 4px;cursor:pointer !important;\"><span class=\"aptureLinkIcon\" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:11px !important;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;background-image:url(http://cdn.apture.com/media/imgs/link_icons.gif?v12) !important;background-position:100% -1348px;background-repeat:no-repeat no-repeat !important;\">&nbsp;</span><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grady%20Booch\" class=\"aptureLink snap_noshots\" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:0px !important;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;\">格雷迪·布奇（Grady Booch）</a></span>称为简单之幻象的东西。说是假象是因为优质的软件其建设基本上都是复杂的，但抽象化这种复杂性正是像CallFire这样的初创企业所面临的挑战。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我们总喜欢认定自己很<a href=\"http://www.ics.uci.edu/callfire\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">特别</a>，但却很难做到独一无二。有许多聪明人都在致力于解决某些真正的云语音问题。尽管如此，无论你在招人还是找工作，好好看看这个团队，因为任何人都将告诉你这一点：即便身处地狱，好的团队也能把你拉回战壕。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><small style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><a href=\"http://www.sxc.hu/photo/485645\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">vierdrie</a>供图</small></em></p> </div> </span><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/博贤/142008#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/160822/142159?from=rss_related\">童女经验</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/158447/141940?from=rss_related\">女孩悄悄话：女孩的语言能力更强吗？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/41906/141957?from=rss_related\">女性的语言能力真的更好吗？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/161833/141067?from=rss_related\">欧元区经济危机的历史教训【外交事务（一家之言）】</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/59868/105676?from=rss_related\">青少年自杀：网络的侵害（推荐）</a></p>") (content:encoded nil "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/start/2010/10/lessons-in-cloud-telephony-a-startup-case-study.php\">Lessons in Cloud Telephony: A Startup Case Study</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/博贤\">boxi</a></p><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:21px;font-size:14px;\"><div class=\"asset-body\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;clear:both;font:normal normal normal 14px/0.9em arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:1.5em;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><img src=\"http://rww.readwriteweb.netdna-cdn.com/whitedialphone.png\" align=\"left\" alt=\"\" border=\"0\" /><br /> </p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">尽管有关云的成本效益分析以及经济理论的文字已经铺天盖地，但其建设团队却甚少提及。本博文要讲正是这样的一只团队，以及其中一位老手的经验之谈。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">当讨论云电话的时候，有很多理由需要关注于人的因素。这不仅在于我们是在跟一种传统的媒介打交道（想想看：电话已经出现了100多年了），还在于它是一个高度管制的东西，这意味着任何云语音供应商实际上都是一家集成公司。</p> </div> <div id=\"more\" class=\"asset-more\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;clear:both;font:normal normal normal 14px/0.9em arial, helvetica, sans-serif;line-height:1.5em;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">客座作者芬纳卡兰（TJ Thinakaran）是CallFire'的COO。CallFire是一家云语音的初创企业，最近在</p> <em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\">INC500的5000家成长最快的公司排行榜中位列</p> </em></em><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\"><a href=\"http://www.inc.com/inc5000/profile/callfire\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">285</a>，在通信业中排在第15位。本文是其个人</p> </em></span></span><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.8;position:relative;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\"><a href=\"http://www.readwriteweb.com/start/2010/10/www.onetj.com\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">博客</a></p> </em></em></em></em></span><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;line-height:21px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;display:inline !important;\">观点的删节版。</p> </em></em></span></em> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-style:normal;\">云电话解决方案是在若干电话公司和用户之间搭建的管道，屏蔽了语音的复杂性，给人以简单的错觉。如果你认为这种无缝的集成是件简单的工作，把你的电话号码拨接到谷歌语音试试。结果很有可能是，除非你是<a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2009/08/09/how-i-learned-to-quit-the-iphone-and-love-google-voice/\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">迈克尔·阿灵顿（Michael Arrington）</a>，否则有你好过的。</span></p> </em> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">云的理念</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">由于云电话是一种集成的方式，创建此类解决方案的团队不得不既要有非常广泛的技能，同时还要有非常专业的理念。因此尽管对Linux内核调优、按需部署解决方案、发布复杂功能以及跟踪经过我们系统的上百万个电话中的任何一个等这些都是关键技能，更为重要的是团队横向思考的倾向以及边界规避的能力。简而言之，这是一种涉猎到许多不同的主题和领域，并将它们整合为一个针对所有不明确问题的非线性的解决方案。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<div class=\"pullquote\" style=\"margin-top:10px;margin-right:10px;margin-bottom:10px;margin-left:10px;padding-top:10px;padding-right:10px;padding-bottom:10px;padding-left:10px;float:right;width:275px;font-size:1.2em;background-color:#ffe7e7;font-family:georgia, serif;font-style:italic;line-height:1.45em;\">傲慢反之，则是弃教养于不顾的信心。是愚蠢的自信。是无惧自己知识深浅、财力强弱而直面问题并解决问题的信念。</div> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">无论如何，这些技能组合以及思维方式都是难以成为独一无二的。实际上，在一项经常被引用的MIT经典<a href=\"http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=6100\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">研究</a>里，据证实，高效能的工程师最有可能是那些能与专业外的专家协商的人。 他们意识到自己问题领域的复杂性，并知道要利用多学科框架来解决上述问题的需求。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">这在跟以对变化谨慎著称的电信运营商打交道时尤为重要。作为一名前IBM人，我有幸跟许多符合模式的高效能的人士一起工作；然而，当我离开蓝色巨人（译注：指IBM）到CallFire时，我知道了云电话初创企业需要一种略为不同的性格类型。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训1：无知</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">说起来有点令人震惊，但CallFire一开始并没有构思出一个特别的商业计划或者特性。尽管我们拥有丰富的技术经验，但对于电信却是知之甚少。CallFire乃应客户之需而诞生的，其关注点在于交付跟客户有关的功能特性。一些行动都来自于这一个关注点。这是非常短期、非常快节奏的，几乎没有时间来考虑远期愿景和使命宣言。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">学会接受“不知道”这种感觉是困难的，尤其是由于你的一切成年生活都被刻意营造为专家时。你获得了自己的首份工作，通过展示自己所知道而非不知道的东西来塑造个人的职业生涯。不过，企业家精神在于不断去发现自己的无知。让你不断前行的，是对解决问题的关注，以及对自己产品的激情。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">所以，尽管我们也许并没有一个商业计划，但我们对业务的关注永不缺乏。许多的解决方案和手段并不漂亮，但正如牧牛竞技的信条所言，有时候你得“忘掉那该死的规矩，制住那头牛就行”。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训2：傲慢</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我学到的另一种性格方面的教训是，你要表现出一定程度的傲慢，好让别人知道你是认真的。信心转变成傲慢有一条清晰的接线，而初创企业经常会触碰那条线。信心是一种基本的信仰，你了解需要完成的东西是什么，因为你有合适的工具、受过良好的培训，可以那样做。傲慢反之，则是弃教养于不顾的信心。是愚蠢的自信。是无惧自己知识深浅、财力强弱而直面问题并解决之的信念。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">傲慢也是对规模的一种很好的心里代偿方式。在IBM的时候，你必须谦虚，因为你资源庞大、弹药充足，被视为一头800磅重的大猩猩，这意味着一丝傲慢表现都将令客户疏远。然而作为初创企业，你没有这种品牌认知度，因此坐在你对面的那个人很容易就会把你的谦卑误以为是缺乏能力。这会传染且是致命的，必须不惜一切代价加以避免。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">记住，我不是在为傲慢开一张空头支票。从错误中学习的意愿，以及倾听客户需求需要高度的谦逊，这对于公司的生存来说同样至关重要。然而，当你还在起步阶段时，你要应对那么多的<a href=\"http://www.ted.com/talks/richard_st_john_s_8_secrets_of_success.html\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">批评、拒绝、小人还有压力（C.R.A.P）</a>，光有信心并不能成事。你得脸皮够厚，把这一切抛诸脑后，然后不断开拓进取。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">教训3：激情</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我有幸跟工作努力、充满激情的一群人共事。但我要说这一点：在初创企业，激情并非可选部分。而是生存的必要条件。在IBM，我可能一样夜以继日、牺牲周末的时间，但在内心深处我知道，如果有个周末我不干活，或者某天5点钟就回家，股票并不会就此下挫。反之，在CallFire工作就不一样了，需要不断的努力工作，没有激情的根本无法难以为继。初创在工作日运作，却是在周末建设好的。每个周末不花时间去建设，下一周就会以失去机会表现出来。这种持之以恒的努力要是没有激情，绝对难以为继。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">激情给人以希望，让工作自己成为回报，并提供了需要的专注。在建设一家公司时尤其如此，因为有那么多事情需要你自己亲力亲为去打造，光靠努力工作是没有机会的。工作再刻苦，如果没有激情，公司都将没有冷效率。</p> <h2 style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0.2em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;font-size:1.3em;font-weight:bold;text-align:left;line-height:1.2em;color:#000000;\">软件是苦差</h2> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">事实上，编写出优质的软件已经成为，且永远都是一件艰苦的工作。云语音的秘诀是，如果有的话，创造出被&nbsp;<span id=\"apture_prvw1\" class=\"aptureLink \" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:0px !important;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;border-top-left-radius:4px 4px;border-top-right-radius:4px 4px;border-bottom-right-radius:4px 4px;border-bottom-left-radius:4px 4px;cursor:pointer !important;\"><span class=\"aptureLinkIcon\" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:11px !important;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;background-image:url(http://cdn.apture.com/media/imgs/link_icons.gif?v12) !important;background-position:100% -1348px;background-repeat:no-repeat no-repeat !important;\">&nbsp;</span><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grady%20Booch\" class=\"aptureLink snap_noshots\" style=\"margin-top:0px !important;margin-right:0px !important;margin-bottom:0px !important;margin-left:0px !important;padding-top:0px !important;padding-right:0px !important;padding-bottom:0px !important;padding-left:0px !important;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;display:inline !important;border-top-width:0px !important;border-right-width:0px !important;border-bottom-width:0px !important;border-left-width:0px !important;border-style:initial !important;border-color:initial !important;float:none !important;\">格雷迪·布奇（Grady Booch）</a></span>称为简单之幻象的东西。说是假象是因为优质的软件其建设基本上都是复杂的，但抽象化这种复杂性正是像CallFire这样的初创企业所面临的挑战。</p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\">我们总喜欢认定自己很<a href=\"http://www.ics.uci.edu/callfire\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">特别</a>，但却很难做到独一无二。有许多聪明人都在致力于解决某些真正的云语音问题。尽管如此，无论你在招人还是找工作，好好看看这个团队，因为任何人都将告诉你这一点：即便身处地狱，好的团队也能把你拉回战壕。</p> <p style=\"margin-top:1em;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-align:left;\"><em style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><small style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;\"><a href=\"http://www.sxc.hu/photo/485645\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;text-decoration:none;outline-style:none;outline-width:initial;outline-color:initial;color:#cc0000;cursor:pointer;\">vierdrie</a>供图</small></em></p> </div> </span><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/博贤/142008#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/160822/142159?from=rss_related\">童女经验</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/158447/141940?from=rss_related\">女孩悄悄话：女孩的语言能力更强吗？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/41906/141957?from=rss_related\">女性的语言能力真的更好吗？</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/161833/141067?from=rss_related\">欧元区经济危机的历史教训【外交事务（一家之言）】</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/59868/105676?from=rss_related\">青少年自杀：网络的侵害（推荐）</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422677564/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/博贤/142008\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422677564/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422677564/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>") (pubDate nil "Tue, 12 Oct 2010 11:10:08 +0800") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142008") (dc:creator nil "boxi") (fs:srclink nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/博贤/142008") (fs:srcfeed nil "http://www.yeeyan.org/feed/category/410") (fs:itemid nil "feedsky/yeeyan-tech/~8024233/422677564/5032246"))) ("概念小汽车iMove - 来自苹果的灵感" "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/automotive-design/concept-car-imove-inspired-by-apple/\">Concept Car “iMove” – Inspired by Apple</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/155419\">MazingTech</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/general.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<blockquote>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;How would look like a car invented and designed by Apple? Italy based auto designer<span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color:#000000;\"><blockquote style=\"display:inline !important;\"><a onclick=\"javascript:pageTracker._trackPageview('/outgoing/liviutudoran.blogspot.com/');\" href=\"http://liviutudoran.blogspot.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Liviu Tudoran</a></blockquote> </span>has taken inspiration from the Apple Macintosh products and designed a concept car called iMove for the year 2020. This car will be electric, of course, and will feature the same general design lines like all the latest Macintosh products. Most of the car body is covered with transparent materials, so that even under the roof the driver get a cabriolet feeling. This transparent material is also a solar panel. iMove will be able to seat three passengers and will feature an innovative luggage storage space. The concept will also offer various possibilities for customization, so the owners will be able to change the car’s appliance according to its own preferences.</blockquote> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;如果苹果要创造设计汽车，最后看起来会是怎么样的呢？意大利汽车设计师Liviu Tudoran已从苹果Macintosh产品的灵感设计出了2020年的名为iMove的概念车。这将是一辆电动车，当然的，将具有所有最新Macintosh产品一样的设计风格。大部分的车身覆盖着透明材料，使即使在盖上车顶，司机也会得到敞篷车的感觉。这种透明材料同时也是太阳能电池板。 iMove将可以乘坐三名乘客，并配备有创新的行李储存空间。这概念车也将提供定制带来的各种可能性，因此，车主可以根据自己的喜好改变车的外观。 </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/01.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/02.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/03.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/04.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/05.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/06.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"322\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/07.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"342\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/08.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"347\" alt=\"Apple car\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;<object style=\"height:366px;width:600px;\" width=\"600\" height=\"366\"></object></p> <p>来源：<span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"line-height:21px;\"><a href=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/automotive-design/concept-car-imove-inspired-by-apple/\">beautifullife.info</a></span></p> <p>编译：<a href=\"http://www.mazingtech.com\" target=\"_blank\">MazingTech</a></p><p><a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/155419/142341#newComment\">添加新评论</a></p><p><strong>相关文章：</strong></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/159598/141531?from=rss_related\">为何iPad在中国会成功</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/160937/141933?from=rss_related\">美国《新闻周刊》杂志网站——Android入侵：Android正在如何改变移动计算领域？（下）</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/160937/141929?from=rss_related\">美国《新闻周刊》杂志网站——Android入侵：Android正在如何改变移动计算领域？（上）</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/178539/141664?from=rss_related\">平板电脑市场群雄逐鹿，紧追业界之王苹果公司</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://article.yeeyan.org/view/174487/141620?from=rss_related\">苹果iOS在BlackBerry和Windows Mobile夹击中艰难前行</a></p><img src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/t1/422733115/yeeyan-tech/feedsky/s.gif?r=http://article.yeeyan.org/view/155419/142341\" border=\"0\" height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"position:absolute\" /><p class=\"fswww1\"><a href=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/l/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733115/art01.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img border=\"0\" ismap=\"ismap\" src=\"http://www1.feedsky.com/r/i/feedsky/yeeyan-tech/422733115/art01.gif\" onerror=\"this.style.display='none'\" /></a></p>" "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/155419/142341" (19635 51876) old 7 nil nil ((title nil "概念小汽车iMove - 来自苹果的灵感") (link nil "http://article.yeeyan.org/view/155419/142341") (created ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T02:40:36+00:00") (issued ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T02:40:36+00:00") (modified ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "2010-10-12T02:40:36+00:00") (id ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) "tag:feed.yeeyan.org:translation/142341") (author ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom")) (name nil "MazingTech") (uri nil "http://space.yeeyan.org/u/155419")) (content ((xmlns . "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom") (type . "html")) "<p>原作者：<br />来源<a href=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/automotive-design/concept-car-imove-inspired-by-apple/\">Concept Car “iMove” – Inspired by Apple</a><br/>译者<a href=\"http://space.yeeyan.org/u/155419\">MazingTech</a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/general.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> &nbsp;&nbsp;<blockquote>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;How would look like a car invented and designed by Apple? Italy based auto designer<span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"color:#000000;\"><blockquote style=\"display:inline !important;\"><a onclick=\"javascript:pageTracker._trackPageview('/outgoing/liviutudoran.blogspot.com/');\" href=\"http://liviutudoran.blogspot.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Liviu Tudoran</a></blockquote> </span>has taken inspiration from the Apple Macintosh products and designed a concept car called iMove for the year 2020. This car will be electric, of course, and will feature the same general design lines like all the latest Macintosh products. Most of the car body is covered with transparent materials, so that even under the roof the driver get a cabriolet feeling. This transparent material is also a solar panel. iMove will be able to seat three passengers and will feature an innovative luggage storage space. The concept will also offer various possibilities for customization, so the owners will be able to change the car’s appliance according to its own preferences.</blockquote> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;如果苹果要创造设计汽车，最后看起来会是怎么样的呢？意大利汽车设计师Liviu Tudoran已从苹果Macintosh产品的灵感设计出了2020年的名为iMove的概念车。这将是一辆电动车，当然的，将具有所有最新Macintosh产品一样的设计风格。大部分的车身覆盖着透明材料，使即使在盖上车顶，司机也会得到敞篷车的感觉。这种透明材料同时也是太阳能电池板。 iMove将可以乘坐三名乘客，并配备有创新的行李储存空间。这概念车也将提供定制带来的各种可能性，因此，车主可以根据自己的喜好改变车的外观。 </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/01.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/02.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/03.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/11/04.jpg\" width=\"600\" height=\"338\" alt=\"Apple car\" /> </p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src=\"http://www.beautifullife.info/wp-content/uploads/